er -->\n\n[[Category:2018 singles]]\n[[Category:2018 songs]]\n[[Category:Lauren Daigle songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jason Ingram]]\n", "name_user": "John Meadow", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWeekly charts", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Still_Rolling_Stones"}
{"title_page": "The Witch (1916 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1916 American film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Witch\n| image          = Film_still_of_actress_Nance_O'Neil_as_Zora_being_accused_of_sorcery,_The_Witch,_1916.jpg\n| image_size     = 240px\n| caption        = [[Film still]] showing the title character Zora ([[Nance O'Neil]]) being accused of witchcraft\n| director       = [[Frank Powell]]\n| producer       = [[William Fox (producer)|William Fox]]\n| based on       =  {{based on|''La Sorci\u00e8re''|[[Victorien Sardou]]}}\n| screenplay     =  Frank Powell\n| starring       =  [[Nance O'Neil]]<br>[[Alfred Hickman]]<br>Frank Russell\n| cinematography = \n| editing        =\n| distributor    = [[Fox Film Corporation]] \n| released       = February 27, 1916\n| runtime        = 5 reels (approximately 5,000 feet; 50-60 mins.)<ref>[http://archive.org/details/motography152elec/page/781 \"Feature Programs: Fox/ The Witch\"], ''Motography'' (Chicago, Illinois), April 1, 1916, p. 781. [[Internet Archive]], San Francisco, California. Retrieved January 13, 2020.</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = Silent with English [[intertitle]]s\n| budget         =\n| gross          =\n}}\n'''''The Witch''''' is a [[Lost film|lost]] 1916 American [[silent film|silent]] [[drama film|drama]] film directed by [[Frank Powell]], produced by [[Fox Film Corporation]], and starring [[Nance O'Neil]], [[Alfred Hickman]], and Frank Russell. Based on the 1903 play ''La Sorci\u00e8re'' (''The [[wikt:sorceress|Sorceress]]'') by French [[dramatist]] [[Victorien Sardou]], this adaptation portrayed the challenges facing a young woman living in a territory in [[Mexico]] wracked by military and social unrest. It was filmed at Fox's studio in [[Fort Lee, New Jersey]], where a Mexican village was constructed on the company's [[backlot]] and used as the principal set for outdoor scenes.\n\n[[The Library of Congress]] includes the film among the [[National Film Preservation Board]]'s updated 2019 list of \"7,200 Lost U.S. Silent Feature Films\" produced between 1912 and 1929.<ref name=\"LOClost\">[http://www.loc.gov/static/programs/national-film-preservation-board/documents/SFF-LostFilmsList102319.pdf \"7,200 Lost U.S. Silent Feature Films (1912-29) National Film Preservation Board\"], running updated list (current as of October 23, 2019), \"Witch, The (1916), Frank Powell\", p. 153, film number 7016. National Film Preservation Board, Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. Retrieved December 23, 2019.</ref><ref>[http://memory.loc.gov/diglib/ihas/html/silentfilms/silentfilms-home.html \"American Silent Feature Film: Database From the report 'The Survival of American Silent Feature Films: 1912-1929'\"], searchable database that includes nearly 11,000 titles. Library of Congress. Library of Congress. Retrieved January 13, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nWith its storyline set in early twentieth-century Mexico, this lost film portrayed the plight of Zora Fernandez (Nance O'Neil), a beautiful and exotic woman who becomes entangled in a love affair and is persecuted by local officials following an armed uprising. Her father, Dr. Fernandez (Frank Russell), is a physician and also a general who leads an insurrection against General Mendoza ([[Alfred Hickman]]), the military governor of the surrounding territory. The doctor and his forces are defeated, and he dies in battle. The victorious Mendoza now resents Zora for her past indifference to his romantic advances and suspects she may try to oppose his authority as well. The governor is concerned too about Zora's reputation as a sorceress, most notably for her abilities to cast spells and concoct miraculous potions. In reality, her father, as a medical doctor, had taught her [[hypnosis]] and how to treat various illnesses. Those abilities, however, are viewed by most of the residents in her village as [[supernatural]] and forms of [[witchcraft]].<ref>This plot summary is composed from a compilation of plot and scene descriptions of ''The Witch'' included in reports and reviews published in a variety of trade publications and newpapers between August 1915 and March 1916.</ref>\n\nTo isolate the \"witch\", Governor Mendoza forces Zora to leave her village and then issues a proclamation warning citizens that any women who associate with her will be imprisoned for life; men who do so will be immediately hung. Zora, despite being ostracized, continues to help the rural poor and sick by dispensing herbal medicines and using her \"magical mental power\".<ref name=\"Moto\">Graves, George W. (1916). [http://archive.org/stream/motography151elec#page/712/mode/2up \"The Witch\"], review, ''Motography'', March 26, 1916, p. 713. Internet Archive. Retrieved January 2, 2020.</ref> When Mendoza's daughter Dolores (Jane Miller) begins to suffer from being \"addicted to [[somnambulism|walking in her sleep]]\", her attending nurse secretly sends for the witch to come cure her.<ref name=\"Moto\"/> Zora slips into the governor's palace with the help of the nurse and then uses her \"mastery of hypnosis\" to cure the young woman. Returning to her \"secluded abode\" outside the village, Zora now meets Lieutenant Riques, a prominent official's son.<ref name=\"Moto\"/> They fall in love, although she is unaware that the handsome soldier is engaged to marry Dolores.\n\nZora later learns of Riques' impending marriage, becomes angry, and quietly goes back to the governor's palace the night before the wedding on the pretext of checking on her patient. Using hypnosis again, Zora puts Dolores into a trance from which \"she will never wake unless at the call of her power.\"<ref name=\"TMPW\">Judson, Hanford C. (1916). [http://archive.org/details/movingpicturewor27newy/page/1846 \"'The Witch'\"], review, ''[[The Moving Picture World]]'', March 18, 1916, pp. 1845-1846. Internet Archive. Retrieved January 5, 2020.</ref> Acquaintances of Zora and Riques now betray the clandestine lovers and reveal their affair. The couple are arrested and tried, but Zora saves Riques from hanging by assuming all the blame and lying that she had captured his heart by casting a spell on him, one that he could not resist. Zora is then convicted, sentenced to death for witchcraft, and carried away by a mob to be burned at the stake. Zora is about to be executed when Dolores's nurse rushes in to inform the governor that his daughter is in a deep sleep at his palace, cannot be awakened, and only Zora can save her. When offered her freedom in exchange for releasing Dolores from her [[coma]]-like condition, Zora agrees and awakens the governor's daughter. Mendoza then banishes the witch forever from the region.<ref>Plot summaries and reviews of the film in trade publications and newspapers in 1915 and 1916 include descriptions of two dramatically different endings to the production. The version more often given is that Zora in the final scenes is released by officials but permanently \"cast out\" from her village and the region. Some other news and trade publications, however, such as ''[[The Baltimore Sun|The Sun]]'' in Baltimore and the New York-based trade journals ''The Moving Picture World'' and ''[[Motion Picture News]]'', state in their reviews that she is burned at the stake at the film's conclusion.</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n\n[[File:Film_still_of_actresses_Nance_O'Neil_(left)_and_Jane_Miller_in_\"The_Witch\"_(1916).jpeg|thumb|210px|right|Still of O'Neil (left) in scene in which her character Zora hypnotized Dolores, the military governor's daughter (Jane Miller)]]\n\n*[[Nance O'Neil]] as Zora Fernandez\n*[[Alfred Hickman]]\tas General Mendoza\n*Frank Russell as General Fernandez\n*[[Macey Harlam]] as Pedro\n*Ada Neville as Isha\n*Jane Miller as Dolores Mendoza\n*Sadie Gross as dancer\n*[[Stuart Holmes]], undetermined role\n*Harry Kendall, undetermined role \n*Victor Benoit, undetermined role\n*Robert Payne, undetermined role<ref>\"Feature Programs: Fox\", identifications of principal cast, ''Motography'', March 4, 1916, p. 551. Internet Archive.</ref>\n*June Janin, undetermined role\n*Adah Sherman, undetermined role\n*Salvatore Maltess, undetermined role\n\n==Production==\nThe film's 1916 [[copyright]] registration (LP7713) confirms that director and \"[[Screenwriter|scenarist]]\" Frank Powell based his script on Victorien Sardou's play ''La Sorci\u00e8re'', which had premiered in [[Paris, France|Paris]] at the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de la Ville|Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Sarah Bernhardt]] on December 15, 1903.<ref name=\"AFI\">[http://catalog.afi.com/Film/16838-THE-WITCH?sid=e349a584-7089-4005-a49c-e6e37489ee70&sr=1.1701436&cp=1&pos=0 \"The Witch (1916)\"], American Film Institute (AFI), Los Angeles, California. Retrieved December 21, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"NYT1903\">\"Sardou Play Triumphs: 'La sorci\u00e8re' and Sarah Bernhardt Accorded a Great Ovation in Paris\", ''The New York Times'', December 16, 1903, p. 8. [[ProQuest]] Historical Newspapers (subscribed reference service), Ann Arbor, Michigan.</ref> The original plot of Sardou's play, as presented in Paris, was set in sixteenth-century [[Toledo, Spain]] with the sorceress \"Zorraya\" portrayed as being of [[Moors|Moorish]] ancestry.<ref name=\"NYT1903\"/><ref>In its coverage of the play's 1903 Parisian premiere, ''The New York Times'' refers to the central character as \"Zorroya\", although the correct spelling of the character's name in Sardou's original work is \"Zorraya\". See the 1904 published French script of ''La sorci\u00e8re''.</ref>  For his film adaptation, Powell made numerous changes to the French dramatist's plot, such as relocating the story to Mexico, advancing its time setting to the early 1900s, simplifying the spelling of Zorroya's name to \"Zora\", and portraying her as a Mexican native.<ref name=\"AFI\"/>\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:Ad_for_1916_film_The_Witch_featuring_Nance_O'Neil.jpeg|thumb|right|Promotion of O'Neil as the \"Empress of Stormy Emotion\", ''Motion Picture News'', March 1916]]\n\nPowell's casting of Nance O'Neil in the title role was viewed by the media and by film studios as a wise and somewhat expected choice given O'Neil's acting reputation as \"America's [[Sarah Bernhardt]]\" and her previous experience portraying Zorraya in stage productions of ''La Sorci\u00e8re''.<ref name=\"AZR\">\"Nance O'Neil in 'Witch' at Lamara\", ''Arizona Republican'' (Phoenix), March 20, 1916, p. 10. ProQuest.</ref> The respected American playwright and stage director [[David Belasco]] declared O'Neil at the time of the film's production to be \"the greatest of America's emotional actresses\".<ref>[https://ia800900.us.archive.org/BookReader/BookReaderImages.php?zip=/27/items/motionpicturenew121unse/motionpicturenew121unse_jp2.zip&file=motionpicturenew121unse_jp2/motionpicturenew121unse_0610.jp2&scale=4&rotate=0MPN \"'Sin' Scheduled for First Fox One-a-Week\"], ''Motion Picture News'', August 7, 1915, p. 46. Internet Archive. Retrieved January 4, 2020.</ref> ''[[The Arizona Republic]]an'' was one of many newspapers and trade publications in 1916 that expressed interest in seeing her perform the role on screen rather than on stage:{{quote|Miss O'Neil played this part so long and carried it to such triumphant heights in the world of stage art, that it has almost become a part of her. Naturally, to be cast in a character so long and so wonderfully played by her, makes this picture of greater importance than it would be under different conditions.<ref name=\"AZR\"/>}}\nStuart Holmes was one of many cast members in ''The Witch'' whose role is not clearly identified in published production updates or in reviews. The March 6, 1916 issue of the ''[[Courier-Journal]]'' in Louisville, Kentucky does at least provide some information about the scope of Holmes' part. In a profile of the film under \"At The Theaters\", the newspaper reports, \"Stuart Holmes, picturesque in Mexican costuming, has a small part to which he gives distinction by riding a horse as if he and the horse were one.\"<ref>\"At The Theaters/ 'The Witch'\", ''Courier-Journal'' (Louisville, Kentucky), March 6, 1916, p. 4. ProQuest.</ref>\n\nFor his film's battle sequences, crowd scenes, and to populate the production's large Mexican-village set, Powell hired and costumed hundreds of [[Extra (acting)|extra]]s or \"[[wikt:Special:Search/supernumerary|supernumones]]\". The director promised to pay each of them \"a sandwich at noon and a dollar at night\" for a day's work at Fox's studio in Fort Lee, New Jersey.<ref name=\"MPN15b\">[http://archive.org/details/motionpicturenew121unse/page/n625 \"Police Hold Fox Extras In 'Witch' Scene As Oil Rioters\"], ''Motion Picture News'', August 7, 1915, p. 66. Internet Archive. Retrieved December 23, 2019.</ref> In early August 1915, ''Motion Picture News'' reported that New Jersey police had detained and questioned \"three hundred or more extras\" for ''The Witch'' as they disembarked from a New York ferry at Fort Lee to proceed to the studio.<ref name=\"MPN15b\"/> The officers, according to the weekly journal, mistook the \"mob\" to be part of the thousands of employees who that summer were waging a violent strike against a [[Standard Oil]] Company plant in [[Bayonne, New Jersey|Bayonne]].<ref name=\"MPN15b\"/><ref>\"MILITIA TO QUELL BAYONNE RIOTERS; 1 DEAD, MANY HURT: Two Regiments Await Order to Subdue Strikers at Standard Oil's Plant...\", ''The New York Times'', July 22, 1915, p. 1. ProQuest.</ref> After causing a near \"riot\" for delaying the extras, the police finally allowed them to continue to Fox to earn their sandwiches and dollars.<ref name=\"MPN15b\"/>\n\n===Filming and set design===\n[[File:Photograph_of_Director_Frank_Powell_(left)_examining_set_model_for_his_film_The_Witch_(1916).jpeg|thumb|180px|right|Powell (left) examining production model of Mexican village with Turner (center) and Bach, summer 1915]]\n\nThe entire production was filmed in Fort Lee at Fox's facilities located near the intersection of Main Street and Linwood Avenue.<ref>Wander, Erik. [http://patch.com/new-jersey/fortlee/from-the-archives-theda-bara-rock-fox-studio-back-lotd00fd29aa0 \"From the Archives: Theda Bara Rock, Fox Studio Back Lot, Main Street and Linwood Avenue, Circa 1915\"], Arts and Entertainment, ''Patch'', [[Patch Media]], Inc., New York City. Retrieved December 23, 2019.</ref> Rather than going on location, traveling from New Jersey to Mexico with a large company of actors, crew, and other support personnel, Powell in the early months of 1915 had decided to send his scenic designer, J. Alan Turner, to Mexico to locate, photograph, and sketch the architecture, attire, and daily activities in a \"typical village\" there. Then, on his return to Fort Lee, Turner supervised the construction on Fox studio's [[backlot]] a set with full-size replicas of the Mexican buildings he had documented. The trade journal ''[[Motion Picture News]]'' regularly updated its readers on the production's development, noting that Powell spent more than $10,000 on the Mexican set. \"The village\", it reported, \"is the result of the joint efforts of Mr. Powell himself, J. Alan Turner, who is known as a builder of expositions, and William Bach, the technical director of the Fox studios\".<ref name=\"MPN15a\">[http://archive.org/details/motionpicturenew121unse/page/n501 \"'The Witch' Based on Sardou's 'Sorceress', Is Next Fox Medium for Nance O'Neil\"], ''Motion Picture News'', July 31, 1915, p. 68. Internet Archive. Retrieved January 4, 2020.</ref>\n\nThe film's battle sequences and other outdoor scenes were shot in Fort Lee between late June and early August 1915, over six months prior to the five-reeler's release.<ref>In its [http://archive.org/details/variety39-1915-08/page/n15 \"Film Flashes\" news section], ''Variety'' (New York, N.Y.) announces on August 6, 1915 (page 16), \"Frank Powell has completed the new Nance O'Neil release 'The Witch.'\" Retrieved January 13, 2020.</ref> It is likely that Powell chose New Jersey's summer months to film in order to present on screen a landscape that most theater audiences in 1916 would view as a generally plausible setting for Mexico. Impressed by the sheer scale of the production, ''The Arizona Republican'' remarked that Powell \"spared no time or expense\" in developing his project, noting that \"Villages were built, forests were blown up with dynamite, great battle scenes were put on...and months were consumed in rehearsals and filming the various scenes.\"<ref name=\"AZR\"/>\n\n==Release and promotion==\n\n[[File:Ad_for_1916_film_The_Witch.jpeg|thumb|140px|right|Advertisement in ''The Moving Picture World'', March 1916]]\n\nFox Film Corporation heavily promoted ''The Witch'' in trade publications during the last quarter of 1915 and into the following year. After the film was finally released in late February 1916, varying descriptions in the media about the film's ending suggest that Powell created two different conclusions for his production and, at least initially, distributed two versions of ''The Witch'', possibly anticipating that some communities would object to the more sensational final scenes and bar their screening. The Baltimore newspaper ''The Sun'' recounts one version a week after the film's release:{{quote|...At the last instant the Governor stays the burning of Zora at the stake and promises Zora her freedom if she will bring Dolores from her [[Catalepsy|cataleptic]] state. Zora believing the promise, goes to the palace and arouses the girl. When Dolores is safe the Governor throws Zora into prison. Riques, who realizes that he loves Zora more than Dolores, runs away with her. The two are captured after a desperate fight and in the end Zora is put to death by burning at the stake.<ref name=\"Sun16\">\"Shows Nance O'Neil Burned At The Stake: 'The Witch' Includes Battles, Mobs, Hypnotism, Treachery And Love\", ''The Sun'' (Baltimore, Maryland). March 5, 1916: B5. ProQuest.</ref>}}''[[The Moving Picture World]]'' in its coverage of the film's release also informs its readers that Zora \"is put to death\" at the end of the story.<ref>[http://archive.org/details/movingpicturewor27newy/page/1550 \"FOX FILM CORP./The Witch\"], review, ''The Moving Picture World'' (New York, N.Y.), March 4, 1916, pp. 1550, 1552. Internet Archive. Retrieved January 6, 2020.</ref> In Louisville, Kentucky, the reviewer for ''[[The Courier-Journal]]'' apparently saw the same tragic, fiery ending as well, for the newspaper's film critic reports that after Riques and the witch are captured \"Zora calmly pays the penalty.\"<ref>\"THE MOVIE GUIDE\", ''The Courier-Journal'' (Louisville, Kentucky), March 5, 1916, p. C4. ProQuest.</ref> Yet, the \"photoplay\" critic George Graves for the Chicago trade journal ''[[Motography]]'' and Joshua Lowe of the widely read New York-based entertainment paper ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' describe an entirely different finale to the film, one that is more commonly cited in the media in 1916. Graves simply says that after Zora awakens Dorores \"the witch is set free.\"<ref name=\"Moto\"/> Lowe in his March 3 review expresses his frustration with that same \"vague\" ending and even speculates that Powell had created another version of the closing scenes:{{quote|Just what becomes of Zora in the end is left to the imagination, nothing being told. She is simply shown being cast out. The impression is created that a more definite finish was made and proved unsatisfactory and was discarded  in the assembling of the feature.<ref name=\"Variety\">[http://archive.org/details/variety42-1916-03/page/n21 \"The Witch\"], review, '' Variety'', March 3, 1916, p. 23. Internet Archive. Retrieved January 3, 2020.</ref>}}\n\nIt is certainly possible that Powell created and even released two versions of the film given his experiences with controversies and post-release cuts to two other films he directed and Fox released in 1915, just prior to ''The Witch'' going into production: ''[[A Fool There Was (1915 film)|A Fool There Was]]'' and ''[[The Devil's Daughter (1915 film)|The Devil's Daughter]]'', both starring [[Theda Bara]].<ref name=\"Variety2\">[http://archive.org/details/variety39-1915-07/page/n17 \"'Devil's Daughter' Censored\"], ''Variety'', July 2, 1915, p. 19. Internet Archive. Retrieved January 4, 2020.</ref> In its coverage of the production of ''The Witch'' in the summer of 1915, ''Motion Picture News'' describes Nance O'Neil being emotionally and physically overwhelmed during filming by the realism of her execution scene: \"So convincing in fact that Miss O'Neil, whom they burn as a witch, actually fainted at the stake after being jostled over the heads of the angry crowd\".<ref name=\"MPN15b\"/>\n\n==Reception==\nThe film in 1916 received generally positive or mixed reviews in [[trade publications]] and newspapers in various regions of the United States. ''Variety'' found the production's battle scenes and sets impressive and its \"photography and acting all that could be desired.\"<ref name=\"Variety\"/> The trade paper, however, did take issue with some important aspects of the film, most notably with what it viewed as its vague ending and its culturally disconnected, [[Anachronism|anachronistic]] costume choices for O'Neil:{{quote|Considerable mechanical construction must have been required to give the effect of a Mexican village. In fact, the director, Frank Powell, has gone to no end of trouble to secure proper scenic and [[wikt:Special:Search/sartorial|sartorial]] detail. But just why Miss Nance O'Neil, the star, should be clad in [[Cleopatra]] fashion and sleep in her [[Anno Domini|B.C.]] regalia is not explained.<ref name=\"Variety\"/>}}\n\n[[Peter Milne (screenwriter)|Peter Milne]] of ''Motion Picture News'' describes the film overall as \"a strong feature\" in his March 11, 1916 review, although he does find the story hampered in parts by \"overcrowding\" with too many characters and too few closeups to help theater audiences distinguish individual players.<ref name=\"MPN\">Milne, Peter (1916). [http://archive.org/stream/motionpicturenew132unse#page/1472/mode/2up/search/The+Witch \"The Witch\"], review, ''Motion Picture News'', March 11, 1916, p. 1472. New York, N.Y.: Exhibitors' Time, Inc. Internet Archive. Retrieved December 23, 2019.</ref>\n\n[[File:Mob_scene_in_1916_Fox_film_\"The_Witch\".jpeg|thumb|290px|right|Still of the \"Great Mob Scene\" that shows part of the Mexican-village set and some of the hundreds of extras who earned \"a sandwich\" and one dollar a day for their work.<ref name=\"MPN15b\"/>]]\n\n''[[The Moving Picture World]]'' had a mixed reaction to the film as well. The publication found its storyline \"not in itself convincing\" but predicted that most moviegoers would be satisfied by all the action on screen, by what it termed as the \"stir and bustle and thunder in it.\"<ref>[http://archive.org/details/movingpicturewor27newy/page/1853 \"Comments on the Films Exclusively by Our Own Staff / Fox Film Corporation\"], review, ''The Moving Picture World'', March 18, 1916, p. 1853. Retrieved January 6, 2020.</ref> ''Motography'' judged ''The Witch'' to be a \"spectacular production\" with \"a powerful story\".<ref>[http://archive.org/details/motography00test/page/869 \"Notes From All Over\"], ''Motography'', October 23, 1915, p. 869; [http://archive.org/stream/motography151elec#page/551/mode/2up \"Feature Programs: Fox\"], ''Motography'', March 4, 1916, p. 551. Internet Archive. Retrieved December 28, 2019.</ref> In a more indepth review in the March 26 issue of ''Motography'', the journal's \"photoplay\" critic George Graves describes how \"the general excellence\" of the acting, direction, and sets of the production overcome \"weak spots here and there in the film\".<ref name=\"Moto\"/> Reviews in city and regional newspapers in 1916 are largely positive too, with many of those news outlets focusing attention on O'Neil's performance and on the film's elaborate action scenes. In Connecticut, the ''[[Hartford Courant]]'' titles its review \"Nance O'Neil In Strange Picture\" but states that the \"startling drama\" is made remarkable \"by Miss O'Neil\u2019s intense emotional acting\".<ref>NANCE O'NEIL IN STRANGE PICTURE: \"The Witch,\" a Startling Drama, at the Hartford Theater--Theda Bara Coming\n''The Hartford Courant'' (Hartford, Connecticut), August 27, 1916, p. 16. ProQuest.</ref> ''The Sun'' in Baltimore entices moviegoers to see the film by headlining its review with the production's sensational elements, such as \"Nance O'Neil Burned At The Stake\", along with \"Battles, Mobs, Hypnotism, Treachery And Love\".<ref name=\"Sun16\"/>\n\n==\"Lost\" film status==\nNo full prints or partial reels of the film are preserved in the [[Library of Congress]], the [[UCLA Film and Television Archive|UCLA Film Archives]], in the collection of moving images at the [[Museum of Modern Art]], the [[George Eastman Museum]], or in European film repositories.<ref>[http://www.europeanfilmgateway.eu European Film Gateway], a centralized on-line access and referral point to the holdings of film archives throughout the [[European Union]]. Retrieved January 14, 2020.</ref> In its 2019 list of lost silent films released in the United States between 1912 and 1929, the Library of Congress includes ''The Witch''.<ref name=\"LOClost\"/> Stills from the production, in addition to those depicted on this page, do survive as illustrations in 1915 and 1916 publications and provide a visual record of the general content of some scenes in the film.\n\n==References and notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of lost silent films (1915\u20131919)]]\n*[[1937 Fox vault fire]]: In [[Little Ferry, New Jersey]] in July 1937, a catastrophic fire destroyed more than 40,000 reels of negatives and prints at a storage facility for [[20th Century Fox]]. Besides ''The Witch'', other films directed by Frank Powell and featuring Nance O'Neil were among those extensive losses.\n\n==External links==\n* {{AFI film|id=16838|title=The Witch}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=0007574|title=The Witch}} \n* {{tcmdb title|504107|The Witch}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Witch 1916 Film}}\n[[Category:1916 films]]\n[[Category:1910s drama films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Frank Powell]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Fort Lee]]\n[[Category:Fox Film films]]\n[[Category:Lost American films]]\n[[Category:1910s lost films]]\n[[Category:Lost drama films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1916 American film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Witch\n| image          = Film_still_of_actress_Nance_O'Neil_as_Zora_being_accused_of_sorcery,_The_Witch,_1916.jpg\n| image_size     = 240px\n| caption        = [[Film still]] showing the title character Zora ([[Nance O'Neil]]) being accused of witchcraft\n| director       = [[Frank Powell]]\n| producer       = [[William Fox (producer)|William Fox]]\n| based on       =  {{based on|''La Sorci\u00e8re''|[[Victorien Sardou]]}}\n| screenplay     =  Frank Powell\n| starring       =  [[Nance O'Neil]]<br>[[Alfred Hickman]]<br>Frank Russell\n| cinematography = \n| editing        =\n| distributor    = [[Fox Film Corporation]] \n| released       = February 27, 1916\n| runtime        = 5 reels (approximately 5,000 feet; 50-60 mins.)<ref>[http://archive.org/details/motography152elec/page/781 \"Feature Programs: Fox/ The Witch\"], ''Motography'' (Chicago, Illinois), April 1, 1916, p. 781. [[Internet Archive]], San Francisco, California. Retrieved January 13, 2020.</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = Silent with English [[intertitle]]s\n| budget         =\n| gross          =\n}}\n'''''The Witch''''' is a [[Lost film|lost]] 1916 American [[silent film|silent]] [[drama film|drama]] film directed by [[Frank Powell]], produced by [[Fox Film Corporation]], and starring [[Nance O'Neil]], [[Alfred Hickman]], and Frank Russell. Based on the 1903 play ''La Sorci\u00e8re'' (''The [[wikt:sorceress|Sorceress]]'') by French [[dramatist]] [[Victorien Sardou]], this adaptation portrayed the challenges facing a young woman living in a territory in [[Mexico]] wracked by military and social unrest. It was filmed at Fox's studio in [[Fort Lee, New Jersey]], where a Mexican village was constructed on the company's [[backlot]] and used as the principal set for outdoor scenes.\n\n[[The Library of Congress]] includes the film among the [[National Film Preservation Board]]'s updated 2019 list of \"7,200 Lost U.S. Silent Feature Films\" produced between 1912 and 1929.<ref name=\"LOClost\">[http://www.loc.gov/static/programs/national-film-preservation-board/documents/SFF-LostFilmsList102319.pdf \"7,200 Lost U.S. Silent Feature Films (1912-29) National Film Preservation Board\"], running updated list (current as of October 23, 2019), \"Witch, The (1916), Frank Powell\", p. 153, film number 7016. National Film Preservation Board, Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. Retrieved December 23, 2019.</ref><ref>[http://memory.loc.gov/diglib/ihas/html/silentfilms/silentfilms-home.html \"American Silent Feature Film: Database From the report 'The Survival of American Silent Feature Films: 1912-1929'\"], searchable database that includes nearly 11,000 titles. Library of Congress. Library of Congress. Retrieved January 13, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nWith its storyline set in early twentieth-century Mexico, this lost film portrayed the plight of Zora Fernandez (Nance O'Neil), a beautiful and exotic woman who becomes entangled in a love affair and is persecuted by local officials following an armed uprising. Her father, Dr. Fernandez (Frank Russell), is a physician and also a general who leads an insurrection against General Mendoza ([[Alfred Hickman]]), the military governor of the surrounding territory. The doctor and his forces are defeated, and he dies in battle. The victorious Mendoza now resents Zora for her past indifference to his romantic advances and suspects she may try to oppose his authority as well. The governor is concerned too about Zora's reputation as a sorceress, most notably for her abilities to cast spells and concoct miraculous potions. In reality, her father, as a medical doctor, had taught her [[hypnosis]] and how to treat various illnesses. Those abilities, however, are viewed by most of the residents in her village as [[supernatural]] and forms of [[witchcraft]].<ref>This plot summary is composed from a compilation of plot and scene descriptions of ''The Witch'' included in reports and reviews published in a variety of trade publications and newpapers between August 1915 and March 1916.</ref>\n\nTo isolate the \"witch\", Governor Mendoza forces Zora to leave her village and then issues a proclamation warning citizens that any women who associate with her will be imprisoned for life; men who do so will be immediately hung. Zora, despite being ostracized, continues to help the rural poor and sick by dispensing herbal medicines and using her \"magical mental power\".<ref name=\"Moto\">Graves, George W. (1916). [http://archive.org/stream/motography151elec#page/712/mode/2up \"The Witch\"], review, ''Motography'', March 26, 1916, p. 713. Internet Archive. Retrieved January 2, 2020.</ref> When Mendoza's daughter Dolores (Jane Miller) begins to suffer from being \"addicted to [[somnambulism|walking in her sleep]]\", her attending nurse secretly sends for the witch to come cure her.<ref name=\"Moto\"/> Zora slips into the governor's palace with the help of the nurse and then uses her \"mastery of hypnosis\" to cure the young woman. Returning to her \"secluded abode\" outside the village, Zora now meets Lieutenant Riques, a prominent official's son.<ref name=\"Moto\"/> They fall in love, although she is unaware that the handsome soldier is engaged to marry Dolores.\n\nZora later learns of Riques' impending marriage, becomes angry, and quietly goes back to the governor's palace the night before the wedding on the pretext of checking on her patient. Using hypnosis again, Zora puts Dolores into a trance from which \"she will never wake unless at the call of her power.\"<ref name=\"TMPW\">Judson, Hanford C. (1916). [http://archive.org/details/movingpicturewor27newy/page/1846 \"'The Witch'\"], review, ''[[The Moving Picture World]]'', March 18, 1916, pp. 1845-1846. Internet Archive. Retrieved January 5, 2020.</ref> Acquaintances of Zora and Riques now betray the clandestine lovers and reveal their affair. The couple are arrested and tried, but Zora saves Riques from hanging by assuming all the blame and lying that she had captured his heart by casting a spell on him, one that he could not resist. Zora is then convicted, sentenced to death for witchcraft, and carried away by a mob to be burned at the stake. Zora is about to be executed when Dolores's nurse rushes in to inform the governor that his daughter is in a deep sleep at his palace, cannot be awakened, and only Zora can save her. When offered her freedom in exchange for releasing Dolores from her [[coma]]-like condition, Zora agrees and awakens the governor's daughter. Mendoza then banishes the witch forever from the region.<ref>Plot summaries and reviews of the film in trade publications and newspapers in 1915 and 1916 include descriptions of two dramatically different endings to the production. The version more often given is that Zora in the final scenes is released by officials but permanently \"cast out\" from her village and the region. Some other news and trade publications, however, such as ''[[The Baltimore Sun|The Sun]]'' in Baltimore and the New York-based trade journals ''The Moving Picture World'' and ''[[Motion Picture News]]'', state in their reviews that she is burned at the stake at the film's conclusion.</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n\n[[File:Film_still_of_actresses_Nance_O'Neil_(left)_and_Jane_Miller_in_\"The_Witch\"_(1916).jpeg|thumb|210px|right|Still of O'Neil (left) in scene in which her character Zora hypnotized Dolores, the military governor's daughter (Jane Miller)]]\n\n*[[Nance O'Neil]] as Zora Fernandez\n*[[Alfred Hickman]]\tas General Mendoza\n*Frank Russell as General Fernandez\n*[[Macey Harlam]] as Pedro\n*Ada Neville as Isha\n*Jane Miller as Dolores Mendoza\n*Sadie Gross as dancer\n*[[Stuart Holmes]], undetermined role\n*Harry Kendall, undetermined role \n*Victor Benoit, undetermined role\n*Robert Payne, undetermined role<ref>\"Feature Programs: Fox\", identifications of principal cast, ''Motography'', March 4, 1916, p. 551. Internet Archive.</ref>\n*June Janin, undetermined role\n*Adah Sherman, undetermined role\n*Salvatore Maltess, undetermined role\n\n==Production==\nThe film's 1916 [[copyright]] registration (LP7713) confirms that director and \"[[Screenwriter|scenarist]]\" Frank Powell based his script on Victorien Sardou's play ''La Sorci\u00e8re'', which had premiered in [[Paris, France|Paris]] at the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de la Ville|Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Sarah Bernhardt]] on December 15, 1903.<ref name=\"AFI\">[http://catalog.afi.com/Film/16838-THE-WITCH?sid=e349a584-7089-4005-a49c-e6e37489ee70&sr=1.1701436&cp=1&pos=0 \"The Witch (1916)\"], American Film Institute (AFI), Los Angeles, California. Retrieved December 21, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"NYT1903\">\"Sardou Play Triumphs: 'La sorci\u00e8re' and Sarah Bernhardt Accorded a Great Ovation in Paris\", ''The New York Times'', December 16, 1903, p. 8. [[ProQuest]] Historical Newspapers (subscribed reference service), Ann Arbor, Michigan.</ref> The original plot of Sardou's play, as presented in Paris, was set in sixteenth-century [[Toledo, Spain]] with the sorceress \"Zorraya\" portrayed as being of [[Moors|Moorish]] ancestry.<ref name=\"NYT1903\"/><ref>In its coverage of the play's 1903 Parisian premiere, ''The New York Times'' refers to the central character as \"Zorroya\", although the correct spelling of the character's name in Sardou's original work is \"Zorraya\". See the 1904 published French script of ''La sorci\u00e8re''.</ref>  For his film adaptation, Powell made numerous changes to the French dramatist's plot, such as relocating the story to Mexico, advancing its time setting to the early 1900s, simplifying the spelling of Zorroya's name to \"Zora\", and portraying her as a Mexican native.<ref name=\"AFI\"/>\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:Ad_for_1916_film_The_Witch_featuring_Nance_O'Neil.jpeg|thumb|right|Promotion of O'Neil as the \"Empress of Stormy Emotion\", ''Motion Picture News'', March 1916]]\n\nPowell's casting of Nance O'Neil in the title role was viewed by the media and by film studios as a wise and somewhat expected choice given O'Neil's acting reputation as \"America's [[Sarah Bernhardt]]\" and her previous experience portraying Zorraya in stage productions of ''La Sorci\u00e8re''.<ref name=\"AZR\">\"Nance O'Neil in 'Witch' at Lamara\", ''Arizona Republican'' (Phoenix), March 20, 1916, p. 10. ProQuest.</ref> The respected American playwright and stage director [[David Belasco]] declared O'Neil at the time of the film's production to be \"the greatest of America's emotional actresses\".<ref>[https://ia800900.us.archive.org/BookReader/BookReaderImages.php?zip=/27/items/motionpicturenew121unse/motionpicturenew121unse_jp2.zip&file=motionpicturenew121unse_jp2/motionpicturenew121unse_0610.jp2&scale=4&rotate=0MPN \"'Sin' Scheduled for First Fox One-a-Week\"], ''Motion Picture News'', August 7, 1915, p. 46. Internet Archive. Retrieved January 4, 2020.</ref> ''[[The Arizona Republic]]an'' was one of many newspapers and trade publications in 1916 that expressed interest in seeing her perform the role on screen rather than on stage:{{quote|Miss O'Neil played this part so long and carried it to such triumphant heights in the world of stage art, that it has almost become a part of her. Naturally, to be cast in a character so long and so wonderfully played by her, makes this picture of greater importance than it would be under different conditions.<ref name=\"AZR\"/>}}\nStuart Holmes was one of many cast members in ''The Witch'' whose role is not clearly identified in published production updates or in reviews. The March 6, 1916 issue of the ''[[Courier-Journal]]'' in Louisville, Kentucky does at least provide some information about the scope of Holmes' part. In a profile of the film under \"At The Theaters\", the newspaper reports, \"Stuart Holmes, picturesque in Mexican costuming, has a small part to which he gives distinction by riding a horse as if he and the horse were one.\"<ref>\"At The Theaters/ 'The Witch'\", ''Courier-Journal'' (Louisville, Kentucky), March 6, 1916, p. 4. ProQuest.</ref>\n\nFor his film's battle sequences, crowd scenes, and to populate the production's large Mexican-village set, Powell hired and costumed hundreds of [[Extra (acting)|extra]]s or \"[[wikt:Special:Search/supernumerary|supernumones]]\". The director promised to pay each of them \"a sandwich at noon and a dollar at night\" for a day's work at Fox's studio in Fort Lee, New Jersey.<ref name=\"MPN15b\">[http://archive.org/details/motionpicturenew121unse/page/n625 \"Police Hold Fox Extras In 'Witch' Scene As Oil Rioters\"], ''Motion Picture News'', August 7, 1915, p. 66. Internet Archive. Retrieved December 23, 2019.</ref> In early August 1915, ''Motion Picture News'' reported that New Jersey police had detained and questioned \"three hundred or more extras\" for ''The Witch'' as they disembarked from a New York ferry at Fort Lee to proceed to the studio.<ref name=\"MPN15b\"/> The officers, according to the weekly journal, mistook the \"mob\" to be part of the thousands of employees who that summer were waging a violent strike against a [[Standard Oil]] Company plant in [[Bayonne, New Jersey|Bayonne]].<ref name=\"MPN15b\"/><ref>\"MILITIA TO QUELL BAYONNE RIOTERS; 1 DEAD, MANY HURT: Two Regiments Await Order to Subdue Strikers at Standard Oil's Plant...\", ''The New York Times'', July 22, 1915, p. 1. ProQuest.</ref> After causing a near \"riot\" for delaying the extras, the police finally allowed them to continue to Fox to earn their sandwiches and dollars.<ref name=\"MPN15b\"/>\n\n===Filming and set design===\n[[File:Photograph_of_Director_Frank_Powell_(left)_examining_set_model_for_his_film_The_Witch_(1916).jpeg|thumb|180px|right|Powell (left) examining production model of Mexican village with Turner (center) and Bach, summer 1915]]\n\nThe entire production was filmed in Fort Lee at Fox's facilities located near the intersection of Main Street and Linwood Avenue.<ref>Wander, Erik. [http://patch.com/new-jersey/fortlee/from-the-archives-theda-bara-rock-fox-studio-back-lotd00fd29aa0 \"From the Archives: Theda Bara Rock, Fox Studio Back Lot, Main Street and Linwood Avenue, Circa 1915\"], Arts and Entertainment, ''Patch'', [[Patch Media]], Inc., New York City. Retrieved December 23, 2019.</ref> Rather than going on location, traveling from New Jersey to Mexico with a large company of actors, crew, and other support personnel, Powell in the early months of 1915 had decided to send his scenic designer, J. Alan Turner, to Mexico to locate, photograph, and sketch the architecture, attire, and daily activities in a \"typical village\" there. Then, on his return to Fort Lee, Turner supervised the construction on Fox studio's [[backlot]] a set with full-size replicas of the Mexican buildings he had documented. The trade journal ''[[Motion Picture News]]'' regularly updated its readers on the production's development, noting that Powell spent more than $10,000 on the Mexican set. \"The village\", it reported, \"is the result of the joint efforts of Mr. Powell himself, J. Alan Turner, who is known as a builder of expositions, and William Bach, the technical director of the Fox studios\".<ref name=\"MPN15a\">[http://archive.org/details/motionpicturenew121unse/page/n501 \"'The Witch' Based on Sardou's 'Sorceress', Is Next Fox Medium for Nance O'Neil\"], ''Motion Picture News'', July 31, 1915, p. 68. Internet Archive. Retrieved January 4, 2020.</ref>\n\nThe film's battle sequences and other outdoor scenes were shot in Fort Lee between late June and early August 1915, over six months prior to the five-reeler's release.<ref>In its [http://archive.org/details/variety39-1915-08/page/n15 \"Film Flashes\" news section], ''Variety'' (New York, N.Y.) announces on August 6, 1915 (page 16), \"Frank Powell has completed the new Nance O'Neil release 'The Witch.'\" Retrieved January 13, 2020.</ref> It is likely that Powell chose New Jersey's summer months to film in order to present on screen a landscape that most theater audiences in 1916 would view as a generally plausible setting for Mexico. Impressed by the sheer scale of the production, ''The Arizona Republican'' remarked that Powell \"spared no time or expense\" in developing his project, noting that \"Villages were built, forests were blown up with dynamite, great battle scenes were put on...and months were consumed in rehearsals and filming the various scenes.\"<ref name=\"AZR\"/>\n\n==Release and promotion==\n\n[[File:Ad_for_1916_film_The_Witch.jpeg|thumb|140px|right|Advertisement in ''The Moving Picture World'', March 1916]]\n\nFox Film Corporation heavily promoted ''The Witch'' in trade publications during the last quarter of 1915 and into the following year. After the film was finally released in late February 1916, varying descriptions in the media about the film's ending suggest that Powell created two different conclusions for his production and, at least initially, distributed two versions of ''The Witch'', possibly anticipating that some communities would object to the more sensational final scenes and bar their screening. The Baltimore newspaper ''The Sun'' recounts one version a week after the film's release:{{quote|...At the last instant the Governor stays the burning of Zora at the stake and promises Zora her freedom if she will bring Dolores from her [[Catalepsy|cataleptic]] state. Zora believing the promise, goes to the palace and arouses the girl. When Dolores is safe the Governor throws Zora into prison. Riques, who realizes that he loves Zora more than Dolores, runs away with her. The two are captured after a desperate fight and in the end Zora is put to death by burning at the stake.<ref name=\"Sun16\">\"Shows Nance O'Neil Burned At The Stake: 'The Witch' Includes Battles, Mobs, Hypnotism, Treachery And Love\", ''The Sun'' (Baltimore, Maryland). March 5, 1916: B5. ProQuest.</ref>}}''[[The Moving Picture World]]'' in its coverage of the film's release also informs its readers that Zora \"is put to death\" at the end of the story.<ref>[http://archive.org/details/movingpicturewor27newy/page/1550 \"FOX FILM CORP./The Witch\"], review, ''The Moving Picture World'' (New York, N.Y.), March 4, 1916, pp. 1550, 1552. Internet Archive. Retrieved January 6, 2020.</ref> In Louisville, Kentucky, the reviewer for ''[[The Courier-Journal]]'' apparently saw the same tragic, fiery ending as well, for the newspaper's film critic reports that after Riques and the witch are captured \"Zora calmly pays the penalty.\"<ref>\"THE MOVIE GUIDE\", ''The Courier-Journal'' (Louisville, Kentucky), March 5, 1916, p. C4. ProQuest.</ref> Yet, the \"photoplay\" critic George Graves for the Chicago trade journal ''[[Motography]]'' and Joshua Lowe of the widely read New York-based entertainment paper ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' describe an entirely different finale to the film, one that is more commonly cited in the media in 1916. Graves simply says that after Zora awakens Dorores \"the witch is set free.\"<ref name=\"Moto\"/> Lowe in his March 3 review expresses his frustration with that same \"vague\" ending and even speculates that Powell had created another version of the closing scenes:{{quote|Just what becomes of Zora in the end is left to the imagination, nothing being told. She is simply shown being cast out. The impression is created that a more definite finish was made and proved unsatisfactory and was discarded  in the assembling of the feature.<ref name=\"Variety\">[http://archive.org/details/variety42-1916-03/page/n21 \"The Witch\"], review, '' Variety'', March 3, 1916, p. 23. Internet Archive. Retrieved January 3, 2020.</ref>}}\n\nIt is certainly possible that Powell created and even released two versions of the film given his experiences with controversies and post-release cuts to two other films he directed and Fox released in 1915, just prior to ''The Witch'' going into production: ''[[A Fool There Was (1915 film)|A Fool There Was]]'' and ''[[The Devil's Daughter (1915 film)|The Devil's Daughter]]'', both starring [[Theda Bara]].<ref name=\"Variety2\">[http://archive.org/details/variety39-1915-07/page/n17 \"'Devil's Daughter' Censored\"], ''Variety'', July 2, 1915, p. 19. Internet Archive. Retrieved January 4, 2020.</ref> In its coverage of the production of ''The Witch'' in the summer of 1915, ''Motion Picture News'' describes Nance O'Neil being emotionally and physically overwhelmed during filming by the realism of her execution scene: \"So convincing in fact that Miss O'Neil, whom they burn as a witch, actually fainted at the stake after being jostled over the heads of the angry crowd\".<ref name=\"MPN15b\"/>\n\n==Reception==\nThe film in 1916 received generally positive or mixed reviews in [[trade publications]] and newspapers in various regions of the United States. ''Variety'' found the production's battle scenes and sets impressive and its \"photography and acting all that could be desired.\"<ref name=\"Variety\"/> The trade paper, however, did take issue with some important aspects of the film, most notably with what it viewed as its vague ending and its culturally disconnected, [[Anachronism|anachronistic]] costume choices for O'Neil:{{quote|Considerable mechanical construction must have been required to give the effect of a Mexican village. In fact, the director, Frank Powell, has gone to no end of trouble to secure proper scenic and [[wikt:Special:Search/sartorial|sartorial]] detail. But just why Miss Nance O'Neil, the star, should be clad in [[Cleopatra]] fashion and sleep in her [[Anno Domini|B.C.]] regalia is not explained.<ref name=\"Variety\"/>}}\n\n[[Peter Milne (screenwriter)|Peter Milne]] of ''Motion Picture News'' describes the film overall as \"a strong feature\" in his March 11, 1916 review, although he does find the story hampered in parts by \"overcrowding\" with too many characters and too few closeups to help theater audiences distinguish individual players.<ref name=\"MPN\">Milne, Peter (1916). [http://archive.org/stream/motionpicturenew132unse#page/1472/mode/2up/search/The+Witch \"The Witch\"], review, ''Motion Picture News'', March 11, 1916, p. 1472. New York, N.Y.: Exhibitors' Time, Inc. Internet Archive. Retrieved December 23, 2019.</ref>\n\n[[File:Mob_scene_in_1916_Fox_film_\"The_Witch\".jpeg|thumb|290px|right|Still of the \"Great Mob Scene\" that shows part of the Mexican-village set and some of the hundreds of extras who earned \"a sandwich\" and one dollar a day for their work.<ref name=\"MPN15b\"/>]]\n\n''[[The Moving Picture World]]'' had a mixed reaction to the film as well. The publication found its storyline \"not in itself convincing\" but predicted that most moviegoers would be satified by all the action on screen, by what it termed as the \"stir and bustle and thunder in it.\"<ref>[http://archive.org/details/movingpicturewor27newy/page/1853 \"Comments on the Films Exclusively by Our Own Staff / Fox Film Corporation\"], review, ''The Moving Picture World'', March 18, 1916, p. 1853. Retrieved January 6, 2020.</ref> ''Motography'' judged ''The Witch'' to be a \"spectacular production\" with \"a powerful story\".<ref>[http://archive.org/details/motography00test/page/869 \"Notes From All Over\"], ''Motography'', October 23, 1915, p. 869; [http://archive.org/stream/motography151elec#page/551/mode/2up \"Feature Programs: Fox\"], ''Motography'', March 4, 1916, p. 551. Internet Archive. Retrieved December 28, 2019.</ref> In a more indepth review in the March 26 issue of ''Motography'', the journal's \"photoplay\" critic George Graves describes how \"the general excellence\" of the acting, direction, and sets of the production overcome \"weak spots here and there in the film\".<ref name=\"Moto\"/> Reviews in city and regional newspapers in 1916 are largely positive too, with many of those news outlets focusing attention on O'Neil's performance and on the film's elaborate action scenes. In Connecticut, the ''[[Hartford Courant]]'' titles its review \"Nance O'Neil In Strange Picture\" but states that the \"startling drama\" is made remarkable \"by Miss O'Neil\u2019s intense emotional acting\".<ref>NANCE O'NEIL IN STRANGE PICTURE: \"The Witch,\" a Startling Drama, at the Hartford Theater--Theda Bara Coming\n''The Hartford Courant'' (Hartford, Connecticutt), August 27, 1916, p. 16. ProQuest.</ref> ''The Sun'' in Baltimore entices moviegoers to see the film by headlining its review with the production's sensational elements, such as \"Nance O'Neil Burned At The Stake\", along with \"Battles, Mobs, Hypnotism, Treachery And Love\".<ref name=\"Sun16\"/>\n\n==\"Lost\" film status==\nNo full prints or partial reels of the film are preserved in the [[Library of Congress]], the [[UCLA Film and Television Archive|UCLA Film Archives]], in the collection of moving images at the [[Museum of Modern Art]], the [[George Eastman Museum]], or in European film repositories.<ref>[http://www.europeanfilmgateway.eu European Film Gateway], a centralized on-line access and referral point to the holdings of film archives throughout the [[European Union]]. Retrieved January 14, 2020.</ref> In its 2019 list of lost silent films released in the United States between 1912 and 1929, the Library of Congress includes ''The Witch''.<ref name=\"LOClost\"/> Stills from the production, in addition to those depicted on this page, do survive as illustrations in 1915 and 1916 publications and provide a visual record of the general content of some scenes in the film.\n\n==References and notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of lost silent films (1915\u20131919)]]\n*[[1937 Fox vault fire]]: In [[Little Ferry, New Jersey]] in July 1937, a catastrophic fire destroyed more than 40,000 reels of negatives and prints at a storage facilty for [[20th Century Fox]]. Besides ''The Witch'', other films directed by Frank Powell and featuring Nance O'Neil were among those extensive losses.\n\n==External links==\n* {{AFI film|id=16838|title=The Witch}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=0007574|title=The Witch}} \n* {{tcmdb title|504107|The Witch}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Witch 1916 Film}}\n[[Category:1916 films]]\n[[Category:1910s drama films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Frank Powell]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Fort Lee]]\n[[Category:Fox Film films]]\n[[Category:Lost American films]]\n[[Category:1910s lost films]]\n[[Category:Lost drama films]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Witch_(1916_film)"}
{"title_page": "Woodstock 50", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 planned American music festival}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use list-defined references|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox music festival\n| name         = Woodstock 50\n| image        = Woodstock 50 promotional poster.jpg\n| image_size   = \n| alt          = A poster listing the artists with a stylized dove resting on a globe\n| caption      = Original Woodstock 50 promotional poster\n| genre        = \n| dates        = August 16\u201318, 2019 (canceled)\n| location     = \n| coordinates  = \n| years_active = \n| founders     = [[Michael Lang (producer)|Michael Lang]]\n| attendance   = \n| capacity     = \n| website      = {{URL|woodstock.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Woodstock 50''' was a planned American music festival that was scheduled to be held on August 16\u201318, 2019, at [[Merriweather Post Pavilion]] in [[Columbia, Maryland]].<ref name=\"nysaved\">{{cite web |last1=Sisario |first1=Ben |title=Woodstock 50 Festival Is Saved, With Just Weeks to Spare |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/25/arts/music/woodstock-50-maryland.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=25 July 2019 |date=25 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725202841/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/25/arts/music/woodstock-50-maryland.html |archive-date=July 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The event was intended as a commemoration of the 50th anniversary of the [[Woodstock|Woodstock Music & Art Fair]], a landmark festival that was held on August 15\u201317, 1969, in [[Bethel, New York]].  Just prior to its cancellation, it was announced the event had been reduced from three days to one day.<ref name=\"varcyrus\"/> Woodstock 50 was canceled on July 31, 2019, after a series of permit and production issues, venue relocations, and artist cancellations.<ref name=\"w50rip\">{{cite web |last1=Halperin |first1=Shirley |title=Woodstock 50 Officially Off |url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/woodstock-50-off-dead-1203286874/ |website=Variety |accessdate=31 July 2019 |language=en |date=31 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731185730/https://variety.com/2019/music/news/woodstock-50-off-dead-1203286874/ |archive-date=July 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nArtists initially announced for the Woodstock 50 lineup included [[The Killers]], [[Imagine Dragons]], [[Halsey (singer)|Halsey]], [[Miley Cyrus]], [[Robert Plant]], [[The Raconteurs]], [[Cage the Elephant]] and [[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]]. The lineup also included several musical acts that had performed at [[Woodstock|the original 1969 festival]], such as [[Dead & Company]] (featuring three members of the [[Grateful Dead]]), [[John Fogerty]] (with [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]] in 1969), [[Santana (band)|Santana]], [[David Crosby]] (with [[Crosby, Stills & Nash]] in 1969), [[Melanie (singer)|Melanie]], [[John Sebastian]], [[Hot Tuna]] (featuring two members of [[Jefferson Airplane]]), [[Canned Heat]] and [[Country Joe McDonald]] (lead singer of [[Country Joe and the Fish]] in 1969).<ref name=\"rs\">{{cite news |last1=Kreps |first1=Daniel |title=Woodstock 50 Details Full Lineup With Jay-Z, Dead & Company, Killers |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-details-full-lineup-with-jay-z-dead-company-killers-809290/ |accessdate=March 19, 2019 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=March 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320012256/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-details-full-lineup-with-jay-z-dead-company-killers-809290/ |archive-date=March 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWoodstock 50 and its lineup were officially announced in March 2019 but tickets were not released for sale on a previously scheduled date.<ref name=\"nytstock\"/> In late April 2019, a financial backer claimed the festival had been canceled, which was disputed by organizers.<ref name=\"cnnstock\"/> Conflicting media reports ranged from allegations of financial and legal difficulties to an inability to secure proper permits from local officials. In May, a judge ruled that the financiers had no right to cancel the festival, allowing the event to proceed as planned.<ref name=\"ShowGo\"/> The festival was to take place at the [[Watkins Glen International]] racetrack but in June 2019 the venue announced the event would no longer be held there.<ref name=\"watkinsgone\"/> The concert's location was moved to Merriweather Post Pavilion in Maryland on July 25.<ref name=\"bloom1\"/> The next day, all of the artists who had been initially announced as part of the festival's lineup were released from their contracts.<ref name=\"bblineup\"/>\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|Woodstock}}\n[[File:Cars drive through the Esses during the 2014 Sahlen's Six Hours of The Glen.jpg|thumb|right|Part of the [[Watkins Glen International]] racetrack (pictured in 2014), the original planned venue of the festival.]]\n\nWoodstock's co-creator [[Michael Lang (producer)|Michael Lang]] helped organize Woodstock 50.<ref name=\"ap\">{{cite web |url=https://www.apnews.com/05f5f20b964b4df8ad37e55d2a63eda3 |title=Festival co-founder: Lineup for Woodstock 50 coming soon |date=March 7, 2019 |publisher=[[AP News]] |last=Fekadu |first=Mesfin |access-date=March 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326112346/https://apnews.com/05f5f20b964b4df8ad37e55d2a63eda3 |archive-date=March 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lang had been planning to hold a 50th anniversary Woodstock festival in 2019 since at least 2014.<ref name=\"rs2014\">{{cite web |last1=Newman |first1=Jason |title=Woodstock Organizer Plots 50th Anniv. Concert |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-organizer-plotting-50th-anniversary-concert-for-2019-110421/ |website=Rolling Stone |date=30 May 2014}}</ref> He began negotiating with Japanese investment firm [[Dentsu Aegis Network]] in late 2018 to arrange funding for Woodstock 50.<ref name=\"rs1\">{{cite web |last1=Browne |first1=David |last2=Grow |first2=Kory |title=\u2018It Was One Problem After Another\u2019: How Woodstock 50 Turned Into a Disaster |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/woodstock-50-disaster-872320 |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=19 August 2019 |date=18 August 2019}}</ref> Lang was not a producer for the festival, and was instead hired as a consultant by Woodstock 50 LLC, a production company founded by hoteliers Greg Peck and Susan Cronin and a separate entity from Lang's company Woodstock Ventures.<ref name=\"rs1\"/> This arrangement was done so Lang could avoid a [[conflict of interest]] with Woodstock Ventures, which owns the rights to the Woodstock brand.<ref name=\"rs1\"/> Woodstock 50 LLC and Lang entered into a partnership with Dentsu Aegis in December 2018, and licensed the rights to use the Woodstock name from Woodstock Ventures.<ref name=\"rs1\"/> The investment firm was contracted to contribute about $49.1 million to fund the festival, based on Lang's initial estimated attendance number of 150,000 people.<ref name=\"rs1\"/>\n\nIn January 2019, Lang confirmed that he would be organizing a fourth three-day Woodstock festival that would take place in August in [[Watkins Glen, New York]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greene |first1=Andy |title=Three-Day Woodstock Festival From Original Organizer Coming This Summer |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50th-anniversary-michael-lang-775588/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 May 2019 |date=9 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414112739/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50th-anniversary-michael-lang-775588/ |archive-date=April 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Watkins Glen International]] racetrack was chosen as the location of the festival.<ref name=\"racetrack\">{{cite web |last1=Barry |first1=John W. |title=Watkins Glen International to host Woodstock anniversary show in August |url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2019/01/09/woodstock-watkins-glen-international/2524398002/ |website=The Poughkeepsie Journal |accessdate=6 May 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506183040/https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2019/01/09/woodstock-watkins-glen-international/2524398002/ |archive-date=May 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The site had previously hosted three large music festivals; [[Summer Jam at Watkins Glen]] in 1973 and two multi-day concerts organized by the rock band [[Phish]] in 2011 and 2015.<ref name=\"racetrack\"/> In August 2018, a third Phish festival scheduled to be held at the racetrack was canceled by [[New York Department of Health]] officials one day before it was scheduled to begin due to water quality and safety issues at the site following several days of flooding in the [[Finger Lakes]] region.<ref>{{cite web |title=Phish festival Curveball at Watkins Glen canceled over health concerns |url=https://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/2018/08/16/phish-festival-curveball-watkins-glen-canceled-over-health-concerns/1013358002/ |website=Rochester Democrat and Chronicle |accessdate=1 September 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Watkins Glen official: 'This whole valley kind of cleaned itself and went into Seneca Lake' |url=https://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/2018/08/17/phish-curveball-festival-watkins-glen-canceled-water-advisory/1018849002/ |website=Rochester Democrat and Chronicle |accessdate=1 September 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Lang said he planned for a separate water supply to be brought into the Woodstock 50 site to avoid the issues Phish had experienced.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Exclusive: How Woodstock 50 lineup was chosen, and how Watkins Glen won\u2019t repeat \u201999 disaster |url=https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/03/exclusive-how-woodstock-50-lineup-was-chosen-and-how-watkins-glen-wont-repeat-99-disaster.html |website=syracuse.com |accessdate=6 May 2019 |date=25 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506183043/https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/03/exclusive-how-woodstock-50-lineup-was-chosen-and-how-watkins-glen-wont-repeat-99-disaster.html |archive-date=May 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Billboard'' reported that promoters and agents for musical acts had tried to persuade Lang to seek another venue because the site was too far away from large hotels and was seen as a risky location to hold a festival following the circumstances of Phish's cancellation the previous year.<ref name=\"infighting\">{{cite web |last1=Brooks |first1=Dave |title=How Infighting and Delays Caused Woodstock 50 to Come Unwound |url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/legal-and-management/8510917/how-infighting-and-delays-caused-woodstock-50-to-come |website=Billboard |accessdate=11 May 2019 |date=10 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510202009/https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/legal-and-management/8510917/how-infighting-and-delays-caused-woodstock-50-to-come |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn selecting artists for the festival's lineup, Lang planned to book popular contemporary artists alongside musical acts who had appeared in lineup of the original 1969 Woodstock festival.<ref name=\"rs1\"/> In early documents, Lang named several potential headliners for Woodstock 50, including [[Lady Gaga]], [[Bruno Mars]], [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[My Morning Jacket]], [[Bruce Springsteen]], [[Stevie Wonder]], Phish, [[Kendrick Lamar]], [[Green Day]] and [[Drake (musician)|Drake]], none of whom would appear in the announced lineup.<ref name=\"rs1\"/> Lang had also sought [[Paul McCartney]], [[Billy Joel]] and a reunited [[Led Zeppelin]] as headlining performers, but with the exception of Led Zeppelin singer [[Robert Plant]], none of those artists appeared in Woodstock 50's final lineup.<ref name=\"infighting\"/> [[Joan Baez]] told ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' she had been approached to perform at the festival but had turned the offer down.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greene |first1=Andy |title=Joan Baez Reflects on the End of Her Farewell Tour and What\u2019s Next |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/joan-baez-interview-farewell-tour-rolling-thunder-trump-828142/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 May 2019 |date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190501053330/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/joan-baez-interview-farewell-tour-rolling-thunder-trump-828142/ |archive-date=May 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe festival's lineup was announced on March 19, 2019.<ref name=\"rslineup\">{{cite web |last1=Kreps |first1=Daniel |title=Woodstock 50 Details Full Lineup With Jay-Z, Dead & Company, Killers |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-details-full-lineup-with-jay-z-dead-company-killers-809290/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 May 2019 |date=19 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320012256/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-details-full-lineup-with-jay-z-dead-company-killers-809290/ |archive-date=March 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[The Black Keys]] were announced as part of the lineup but pulled out of the festival on April 5 due to a scheduling conflict.<ref name=\"bk\">{{cite web |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/04/the-black-keys-woodstock-canceled/ |title=The Black Keys pull out of Woodstock |date=April 5, 2019 |publisher=[[Consequence of Sound]] |last=Young |first=Alex |access-date=April 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406124735/https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/04/the-black-keys-woodstock-canceled/ |archive-date=April 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Black Keys drummer [[Patrick Carney]] later explained that the band decided to cancel because they had just returned from a hiatus, and \"We realized that we didn\u2019t want our first show back to be in front of 150,000 people in a field without any control.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pareles |first1=Jon |title=For the Black Keys, Rock Lives. It Just Had to Wait |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/27/arts/music/the-black-keys-lets-rock.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=19 August 2019 |date=27 June 2019}}</ref> Following the lineup announcement press conference, Dentsu Aegis privately expressed concern that organizers had spent too much money on acquiring artists other than those that had been previously considered.<ref name=\"rs1\"/>\n\nA second Woodstock 50th anniversary event, held at the [[Bethel Woods Center for the Arts]]\u2014the site of the original 1969 festival\u2014was also scheduled for August 2019. The lineup for the three-day concert program included John Fogerty and Santana, both of whom were included in the Woodstock 50 lineup, as well as [[Ringo Starr]], [[Arlo Guthrie]], [[Edgar Winter]], [[the Doobie Brothers]], [[Blood, Sweat & Tears]], [[Tedeschi Trucks Band]] and [[Grace Potter]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Bethel Woods finalizes Woodstock anniversary weekend lineup |url=https://www.syracuse.com/celebrity-news/2019/04/bethel-woods-finalizes-woodstock-anniversary-weekend-lineup.html |website=syracuse.com |accessdate=7 May 2019 |date=25 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502214911/https://www.syracuse.com/celebrity-news/2019/04/bethel-woods-finalizes-woodstock-anniversary-weekend-lineup.html |archive-date=May 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"bethel1\">{{cite web |title=Bethel Woods Celebrates Woodstock's 50th Anniversary with Santana, John Fogerty, Ringo Starr, Tedeschi Trucks Band and More |url=https://jambands.com/news/2019/08/19/bethel-woods-celebrates-woodstocks-50th-anniversary-with-santana-john-fogerty-ringo-starr-tedeschi-trucks-band-and-more/ |website=Jambands |accessdate=13 September 2019 |date=19 August 2019}}</ref> Lang was not involved with the Bethel concert and filed a cease-and-desist notice against its organizer [[Live Nation (events promoter)|Live Nation]] for promoting it as a rival event to his Woodstock 50 festival.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Urken |first1=Ross |title=Woodstock Backers Hope to Export Brand to Other Countries |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-04-23/woodstock-backers-hope-to-export-brand-to-other-countries |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=7 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507032817/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-04-23/woodstock-backers-hope-to-export-brand-to-other-countries |archive-date=May 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Bethel concerts were held as planned on August 16\u201318.<ref name=\"bethel1\"/>\n\n==Production issues==\n\n===Ticketing and permit delays===\nTickets for the Woodstock 50 festival were supposed to go on sale on April 22, 2019, but no tickets were made available on that date.<ref name=\"nytstock\">{{cite web |last1=Sisario |first1=Ben |title=Woodstock 50\u2019s Backer Says the Festival Is Off. Its Promoter Is Holding Out Hope. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/29/arts/music/woodstock-50th-anniversary-canceled.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=29 April 2019 |date=29 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430025214/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/29/arts/music/woodstock-50th-anniversary-canceled.html |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> At that date, the organizers had yet to receive a mass gathering permit from the New York State Department of Health.<ref>{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 Ticket Sales Delayed as Organizers Lack Required Permit |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/woodstock-50-ticket-sales-delayed-as-organizers-lack-required-permit/ |website=Pitchfork |accessdate=29 April 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430032334/https://pitchfork.com/news/woodstock-50-ticket-sales-delayed-as-organizers-lack-required-permit/ |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> A New York state health regulation forbids advertising for large, overnights events that do not have a permit, which delayed the sale of tickets.<ref name=\"rs1\"/> A mass gathering permit for the festival had been submitted on April 15 but the Department of Health had not approved it at that time.<ref name=\"syra2\"/>\n\n===First cancellation and change of investors===\n\nOn April 29, investors [[Dentsu Aegis Network]], which had been funding Woodstock 50 through its subsidiary Amplifi Live, announced it was no longer funding the festival and that the event had been canceled.<ref>{{cite web |title=Woodstock Organizers Cancel 50th Anniversary Festival |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/festivals/8509091/woodstock-50-festival-cancelled |website=Billboard |accessdate=29 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190429173706/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/festivals/8509091/woodstock-50-festival-cancelled |archive-date=April 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Officials from [[Schuyler County, New York]] also confirmed the cancellation.<ref name=\"cnnstock\">{{cite web |last1=Kaur |first1=Harmeet |title=The Woodstock 50 festival might be canceled, but also it might not be |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/29/entertainment/woodstock-50-festival-canceled-trnd/ |website=CNN |accessdate=29 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430032237/https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/29/entertainment/woodstock-50-festival-canceled-trnd/ |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Dentsu Aegis ceased its involvement after the organizers reduced the capacity of the festival grounds from 100,000 people to 75,000 to accommodate campers after initially promising the company a crowd of 150,000.<ref name=\"syracuse1\">{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Woodstock 50 artists won\u2019t perform; organizer hires Trump attorney (reports) |url=https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/05/woodstock-50-artists-wont-perform-organizer-hires-trump-attorney-reports.html |website=syracuse.com |accessdate=2 May 2019 |date=2 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502214658/https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/05/woodstock-50-artists-wont-perform-organizer-hires-trump-attorney-reports.html |archive-date=May 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later that day, the festival organizers disputed the cancellation in a statement to the ''[[Poughkeepsie Journal]]'' and announced they would be seeking a \"legal remedy\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Has Woodstock 50 been canceled? Organizers argue over status |url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2019/04/29/woodstock-50-cancellation-argument/3616705002/ |website=The Poughkeepsie Journal |accessdate=29 April 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190429192632/https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2019/04/29/woodstock-50-cancellation-argument/3616705002/ |archive-date=April 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On the same day, Lang stated on his Facebook page that, despite the loss of their financial backer, the Woodstock 50 organizers would continue to plan the festival and would seek new investors, and the festival would go ahead as planned.{{refn|group=nb|Michael Lang: \"We are committed to ensuring that the 50th anniversary of Woodstock is marked with a festival deserving of its iconic name and place in American history and culture. Although our financial partner is withdrawing, we will of course be continuing with the planning of the festival and intend to bring on new partners. We would like to acknowledge the State of New York and Schuyler County for all of their hard work and support. The bottom line is, there is going to be a Woodstock 50th Anniversary Festival, as there must be, and it\u2019s going to be a blast!\"}}<ref name=\"jambase.com Woodstock 50 not canceled\">{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 Organizer Michael Lang Says Festival Not Canceled |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/woodstock-50-not-canceled |website=JamBase |accessdate=30 April 2019 |date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430135853/https://www.jambase.com/article/woodstock-50-not-canceled |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Superfly (company)|Superfly]], a production partner of the Woodstock organizers, pulled out of the festival on May 1.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Grow |first1=Kory |title=Woodstock 50 Loses Production Partner Superfly, Putting Festival in Jeopardy |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-loses-superfly-829577/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 May 2019 |date=1 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190501193011/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-loses-superfly-829577/ |archive-date=May 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Superfly also cited changes to the festival's capacity as a reason for its withdrawal.<ref name=\"infighting\"/> Before departing the project, Superfly had estimated  65,000 people as the safest maximum capacity for the festival at Watkins Glen, which was a lower estimate than either Dentsu Aegis or Lang had previously considered.<ref name=\"rs1\"/> Once they received better information of the terrain on the race-track property, they had revised their maximum capacity estimate to 61,000, and stated they would not continue to work on the festival if any planning went ahead for a capacity above that number.<ref name=\"rs1\"/>\n\nAs result of Dentsu Aegis's withdrawal, none of the artists on the lineup were obliged to play at the event because they had made payment agreements through either Dentsu or Amplifi Live rather than the Woodstock promoters.<ref name=\"syracuse1\"/><ref name=\"billboard1\">{{cite web |title=Woodstock Founder Michael Lang Vows Show Will Go On -- But Talent Agencies Say Artists Won't Play |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/8509483/michael-lang-save-woodstock-booking-artists-funding-contracts-agencies |website=Billboard |accessdate=2 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190501215153/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/8509483/michael-lang-save-woodstock-booking-artists-funding-contracts-agencies |archive-date=May 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Representatives from two major talent agencies told ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Dentsu Aegis' decision may have voided the artists' contracts and it was unlikely their clients would be performing at the festival.<ref name=\"billboard1\"/> Following the company's announcement, Dead & Company removed Woodstock 50 from the tour itinerary on their website.<ref>{{cite web |title=John Fogerty Talks Woodstock 50 Potential Cancellation |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/john-fogerty-woodstock-50-cancellation |website=JamBase |accessdate=30 April 2019 |date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430210410/https://www.jambase.com/article/john-fogerty-woodstock-50-cancellation |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> John Fogerty told ''Rolling Stone'' he was disappointed by the announcement and surprised the festival had not secured permits sooner, saying. \"You got the sense there was some shakiness to this whole thing\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Browne |first1=David |title=John Fogerty on Woodstock 50: \u2018There Was Some Shakiness to This Whole Thing\u2019 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/john-fogerty-woodstock-50-cancellation-828793/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=30 April 2019 |date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430210409/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/john-fogerty-woodstock-50-cancellation-828793/ |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''Billboard'' reported on May 6 that CID Entertainment would be producing the festival and that for the event to proceed, Lang would have needed about $30 million by May 10 and a mass gathering permit from the New York Department of Health.<ref>{{cite web |title=To Save Woodstock 50, Michael Lang Plans to Raise $30M by Friday |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8510342/woodstock-50-michael-lang-raise-30m-by-friday-save-festival |website=Billboard |accessdate=7 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506234332/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8510342/woodstock-50-michael-lang-raise-30m-by-friday-save-festival |archive-date=May 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lang also accused Dentsu Aegis of illegally removing $17 million from the festival's bank account, blocking the April 22 ticket sale and attempting to cancel the event without his consent.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Willman |first1=Chris |title=Woodstock Founder Says Japanese Investors Siphoned $17 Million, Sinking Festival |url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/woodstock-founder-michael-lang-claims-investors-dentsu-17-million-1203206596/ |website=Variety |accessdate=7 May 2019 |language=en |date=6 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507022236/https://variety.com/2019/music/news/woodstock-founder-michael-lang-claims-investors-dentsu-17-million-1203206596/ |archive-date=May 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lawyers for the Woodstock organizers requested an injunction against Dentsu Aegis in a New York court on May 9, seeking the return of the disputed $17 million.<ref name=\"injunct\">{{cite web |last1=Browne |first1=David |last2=Grow |first2=Kory |title=Woodstock 50\u2019s Last Stand: 6 Key Things We Learned From New Court Papers |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-dentsu-court-papers-833666/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=11 May 2019 |date=10 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511024436/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-dentsu-court-papers-833666/ |archive-date=May 11, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Amplifi Live filed a counter-claim against Lang on May 13, arguing they had the right to take over the festival and cancel it due to Lang's contractual breaches and logistical misrepresentation.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Grow |first1=Kory |title=\u2018Incompetence and Contractual Breaches.\u2019 Dentsu Fires Back at Woodstock Organizers |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-dentsu-aegis-amplifi-live-response-834737/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=13 May 2019 |date=13 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513230539/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-dentsu-aegis-amplifi-live-response-834737/ |archive-date=May 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA judge in [[New York Supreme Court]] ruled in favor of the Woodstock organizers on May 15 and found that Dentsu Aegis had no legal right to cancel the festival, allowing the event to proceed.<ref name=\"ShowGo\">{{cite web |last1=Browne |first1=David |title=Woodstock 50: The Show Will Go On, But New Funding Needed |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-dentsu-court-decision-835976/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=15 May 2019 |date=15 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516024503/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-dentsu-court-decision-835976/ |archive-date=May 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The judge also ruled that the organizers were not entitled to the $17.8 million that had been removed from the festival's bank account.<ref name=\"ShowGo\"/> On May 17, [[Oppenheimer Holdings]] was announced as the festival's new financial backer.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bloom |first1=Madison |title=Woodstock 50 Gets New Investors |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/woodstock-50-gets-new-investors/ |website=Pitchfork |accessdate=17 May 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517220126/https://pitchfork.com/news/woodstock-50-gets-new-investors/ |archive-date=May 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Following the court ruling, Lang announced that three-day passes to the festival would cost around $400 and that a limited quantity of limited single-day passes would be available, a change from earlier plans in which only three-day passes would be sold.<ref name=\"syra2\">{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Woodstock 50 tickets will be less than $400, organizer now says |url=https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/05/woodstock-50-tickets-will-be-less-than-400-organizer-now-says.html |website=syracuse.com |accessdate=17 May 2019 |date=17 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517153307/https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/05/woodstock-50-tickets-will-be-less-than-400-organizer-now-says.html |archive-date=May 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Loss of original venue===\nWatkins Glen International announced on June 10 it had canceled the contract for the Woodstock 50 festival and that the event would no longer be held at the racetrack.<ref name=\"watkinsgone\">{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 loses site: Watkins Glen racetrack says it won't host |url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2019/06/10/woodstock-50-loses-site-watkins-glen-racetrack-says-wont-host/1413072001/ |website=The Poughkeepsie Journal |accessdate=10 June 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610232115/https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2019/06/10/woodstock-50-loses-site-watkins-glen-racetrack-says-wont-host/1413072001/ |archive-date=June 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The festival had lost its booking at the racetrack because organizers had missed a $150,000 payment.<ref>{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 lost Watkins Glen site after missing $150k payment |url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/entertainment/2019/06/13/woodstock-50-lost-watkins-glen-site-because-missed-150-k-payment/1445880001/ |website=The Poughkeepsie Journal |accessdate=15 June 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190614000842/https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/entertainment/2019/06/13/woodstock-50-lost-watkins-glen-site-because-missed-150-k-payment/1445880001/ |archive-date=June 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The same day, CID Entertainment announced it would also be pulling out of the festival.<ref>{{cite web |title=Second Woodstock 50 Producer Pulls Out After Festival Loses Site |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8515238/woodstock-50-festival-loses-site-producer-cid-entertainment-pulls-out |website=Billboard |accessdate=10 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190611010154/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8515238/woodstock-50-festival-loses-site-producer-cid-entertainment-pulls-out |archive-date=June 11, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> A representative for the festival subsequently told [[Associated Press]] the organizers were in talks with another venue to host the event.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Payne |first1=The Associated Press and Ed |title=Woodstock 50 in doubt: Organizers in talks with another venue |url=https://www.wowt.com/content/news/Woodstock-50-in-doubt-Organizers-in-talks-with-another-venue-511130832.html |website=www.wowt.com |accessdate=12 June 2019 |language=english |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190612033427/https://www.wowt.com/content/news/Woodstock-50-in-doubt-Organizers-in-talks-with-another-venue-511130832.html |archive-date=June 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn late June, the Woodstock organizers applied for a permit to hold a smaller festival at [[Vernon Downs]] horse racing track in [[Vernon, New York]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Woodstock 50 applies for permit at Vernon Downs; up to 65,000 expected (reports) |url=https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/06/woodstock-50-applies-for-permit-at-vernon-downs-up-to-65000-expected-reports.html |website=syracuse.com |accessdate=27 June 2019 |date=26 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190627171701/https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/06/woodstock-50-applies-for-permit-at-vernon-downs-up-to-65000-expected-reports.html |archive-date=June 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The organizers were refused the permit on July 9.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aswad |first1=Jem |title=Woodstock 50 Permit Denied by Latest Proposed Site |url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/woodstock-50-permit-denied-1203262790/ |website=Variety |accessdate=9 July 2019 |language=en |date=9 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709214702/https://variety.com/2019/music/news/woodstock-50-permit-denied-1203262790/ |archive-date=July 9, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The organizers' third appeal was denied by the Vernon planning board on July 16.<ref>{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 Loses Third Appeal In New York\u2019s Vernon |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2051418/woodstock-50-loses-third-appeal-in-new-yorks-vernon/news/ |website=Stereogum |accessdate=20 July 2019 |date=16 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720162404/https://www.stereogum.com/2051418/woodstock-50-loses-third-appeal-in-new-yorks-vernon/news/ |archive-date=July 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Following the ruling, Lang said he would not sue the town to force it to host the event and conceded that the festival would not be held at Vernon Downs.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Woodstock 50 \u2018considering all options\u2019 after CNY town says no |url=https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/07/woodstock-50-considering-all-options-after-cny-town-says-no.html |website=syracuse.com |accessdate=20 July 2019 |date=18 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720162406/https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/07/woodstock-50-considering-all-options-after-cny-town-says-no.html |archive-date=July 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Relocation to Maryland and loss of artist lineup===\n[[File:Merriweather Post Pavilion.jpg|thumb|The festival was to be held at the [[Merriweather Post Pavilion]] (pictured in 2017) in [[Columbia, Maryland]].]]\n\n''[[Bloomberg News]]'' reported on July 25 that the Woodstock organizers had moved the festival to [[Merriweather Post Pavilion]], a venue with a smaller capacity than either of the planned New York sites, in [[Columbia, Maryland]].<ref name=\"bloom1\">{{cite web |last1=Shaw |first1=Lucas |title=Woodstock 50 Festival Moves to Maryland in Bid to Salvage Event |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-25/woodstock-50-festival-moves-to-maryland-in-bid-to-salvage-event |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=25 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725202424/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-25/woodstock-50-festival-moves-to-maryland-in-bid-to-salvage-event |archive-date=July 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Known as \"Woodstock 50 Washington\", the festival would act as a fundraiser for non-profit organizations involved with [[Voter registration campaign|voter registration]] and [[climate change]].<ref name=\"bloom1\"/> Instead of being a ticketed event as originally planned, the festival would be free and concertgoers would  be encouraged to donate to charitable causes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 (Now In Maryland And Without A Lineup) Will Reportedly Be Free |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2052824/woodstock-50-maryland-free/news/ |website=Stereogum |accessdate=27 July 2019 |date=27 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727192016/https://www.stereogum.com/2052824/woodstock-50-maryland-free/news/ |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Seth Hurwitz, co-founder of Merriweather Post Pavilion operator IMP, said his venue would host the festival if organizers presented them with a lineup.<ref name=\"raconteurs\">{{cite web |last1=Newman |first1=Jason |title=The Raconteurs Drop Out of Woodstock 50 as Maryland Still Awaits Permit Application |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-raconteurs-drop-out-woodstock-50-865159/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=30 July 2019 |date=30 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730203611/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-raconteurs-drop-out-woodstock-50-865159/ |archive-date=July 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> A concert headlined by [[The Smashing Pumpkins]] was scheduled to take place at the venue on August 17.<ref>{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 Reportedly Plotting Move To Merriweather Post Pavilion |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/woodstock-50-merriweather-post-pavilion |website=JamBase |accessdate=25 July 2019 |date=25 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725201258/https://www.jambase.com/article/woodstock-50-merriweather-post-pavilion |archive-date=July 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Woodstock 50 would have been reduced from three days to one.<ref name=\"varcyrus\">{{cite web |last1=Aswad |first1=Jem |last2=Halperin |first2=Shirley |title=Miley Cyrus Pulls Out of Woodstock 50 |url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/woodstock-50-one-day-event-common-akon-zombies-1203282632/ |website=Variety |accessdate=31 July 2019 |language=en |date=30 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731000603/https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/woodstock-50-one-day-event-common-akon-zombies-1203282632/ |archive-date=July 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Jay-Z]] and John Fogerty withdrew from the Woodstock 50 lineup shortly after the move to Maryland was announced.<ref name=\"jayzpull\">{{cite web |last1=Nyren |first1=Erin |title=Jay-Z Pulls Out of Woodstock 50 |url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/jay-z-pulls-out-of-woodstock-50-1203281030/ |website=variety.com |accessdate=26 July 2019 |date=26 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726163950/https://variety.com/2019/music/news/jay-z-pulls-out-of-woodstock-50-1203281030/ |archive-date=July 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  On July 26, the promoters released all of the remaining artists on the lineup from their contracted appearances at the relocated festival.<ref name=\"bblineup\">{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 Releases All Artists From Contracts After Maryland Announcement |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/8523989/woodstock-50-releases-all-artists-lineup-maryland-move-venue |website=Billboard |accessdate=26 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726184911/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/8523989/woodstock-50-releases-all-artists-lineup-maryland-move-venue |archive-date=July 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The organizers informed artists of the relocation and contract release in a letter that also requested they still perform at the festival and reminded them of the payment they had received from Dentsu Aegis.<ref name=\"finaldays\">{{cite web |last1=Brooks |first1=Dave |title=Inside the Final Days of Woodstock 50 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/8525668/woodstock-50-final-days-artists-pulling-out-maryland |website=Billboard |accessdate=31 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801023326/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/8525668/woodstock-50-final-days-artists-pulling-out-maryland |archive-date=August 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the following days, Dead & Company, Country Joe McDonald, John Sebastian, Santana, [[The Lumineers]], [[The Raconteurs]], [[Pussy Riot]] and [[Miley Cyrus]] announced they would not be appearing at the relocated festival.<ref name=\"rsdead\">{{cite web |last1=Newman |first1=Jason |title=Dead & Company Drop Out of Woodstock 50 as Artists Flee Beleaguered Festival |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dead-and-co-woodstock-50-864297/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=27 July 2019 |date=26 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727154930/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dead-and-co-woodstock-50-864297/ |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"sinkingship\">{{cite web |last1=Reed |first1=Ryan |title=Woodstock \u201969 Vet Country Joe McDonald Leaps Off \u2018Sinking Ship\u2019 Woodstock 50 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/country-joe-mcdonald-john-sebastian-woodstock-50-865039/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=30 July 2019 |date=30 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730034814/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/country-joe-mcdonald-john-sebastian-woodstock-50-865039/ |archive-date=July 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"raconteurs\"/><ref name=\"varcyrus\"/> Several artists withdrew because they had already scheduled other concerts in the [[Mid-Atlantic (United States)|Mid-Atlantic]] region around the festival weekend and the relocation to Merriweather Post Pavilion conflicted with the [[radius clause]]s for some of those events.<ref name=\"finaldays\"/> A representative for [[The Zombies]] told ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' that the band still planned to perform at Woodstock 50.<ref name=\"varcyrus\"/> On July 30, 17 days before the festival's planned start date, Woodstock 50 organizers had not submitted a permit application to hold an event at Merriweather Post Pavilion.<ref name=\"raconteurs\"/>\n\n===Final cancellation===\nOn July 31, the organizers of Woodstock 50 announced the cancellation of the event.<ref name=\"w50rip\"/> In a press release, representatives said, \"unforeseen setbacks made it impossible to put on a festival we imagined with the great line-up we had booked and the social engagement we were anticipating\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 Is Officially Canceled |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/woodstock-50-is-officially-canceled/ |website=Pitchfork |accessdate=31 July 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731190125/https://pitchfork.com/news/woodstock-50-is-officially-canceled/ |archive-date=July 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lang told media he blamed Dentsu Aegis for the festival's failure and that he was considering further legal action against the firm.<ref name=\"langsyr\">{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Woodstock 50 organizer blames everyone else for canceled festival |url=https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/08/woodstock-50-organizer-blames-everyone-else-for-canceled-festival.html |website=syracuse.com |accessdate=1 August 2019 |date=1 August 2019}}</ref> Despite the cancellation, Lang said he hoped to hold a smaller fundraising event at Merriweather Post Pavilion in late 2019 but was not sure it would bear the Woodstock name.<ref name=\"langsyr\"/>\n\n==Planned line-up==\nEach artist on the Woodstock 50 lineup was paid an advance and the remainder of the payment was held in [[escrow]] until performance or the cancellation of the festival. Alongside the official announcement that the event would not proceed, the organizers suggested the artists donate at least 10 percent of their earnings to [[HeadCount]], a non-profit organization that promotes voter registration. Lang was criticized for trying to make the artists feel guilty.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/woodstock-50-artists-to-receive-millions-despite-cancellation-1203288655/ |title=Woodstock 50 Artists to Receive Millions Despite Festival Cancellation |last=Aswad |first=Shirley Halperin,Jem |last2=Halperin |first2=Shirley |date=2019-08-01 |website=Variety |language=en |access-date=2019-08-15 |last3=Aswad |first3=Jem}}</ref> Prior to July 26, 2019, when remaining artists withdrew ''en masse'' from the event and organizers released them from their contracts,<ref name=\"bblineup\"/> the lineup for the festival was to have included:<ref name=\"rslineup\"/>\n\n;August 16\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[The Killers]]\n*[[Miley Cyrus]]{{refn|group=nb|Cyrus canceled her appearance on July 30.<ref name=\"raconteurs\"/>}}\n*[[Santana (band)|Santana]]{{refn|group=nb|Santana canceled their appearance on July 30.<ref name=\"santana\">{{cite web |last1=Bary |first1=John |title=Woodstock 50: Santana, Lumineers, Raconteurs drop out |url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/2019/07/30/woodstock-50-santana-drop-out/1867203001/ |website=The Poughkeepsie Journal |accessdate=1 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref>}}\n*[[The Lumineers]]{{refn|group=nb|The Lumineers canceled their appearance on July 30.<ref name=\"raconteurs\"/>}}\n*[[The Raconteurs]]{{refn|group=nb|The Raconteurs canceled their appearance on July 30.<ref name=\"raconteurs\"/>}}\n*[[Robert Plant]] and the Sensational Space Shifters\n*[[Nathaniel Rateliff]] and the Night Sweats\n*[[John Fogerty]]{{refn|group=nb|Fogerty canceled his appearance on July 25.<ref name=\"jayzpull\"/>}}\n*[[Run the Jewels]]\n*[[The Head and the Heart]]\n*[[Maggie Rogers]]\n*[[Michael Franti & Spearhead]]\n*[[Bishop Briggs]]\n*[[Anderson East]]\n*[[Akon]]\n*[[Princess Nokia]]\n*[[John Sebastian]]{{refn|group=nb|Sebastian canceled his appearance on July 29.<ref name=\"sinkingship\"/>}}\n*[[Melanie (singer)|Melanie]]\n*[[Grandson (musician)|Grandson]]\n*[[Fever 333]]\n*[[Dorothy (band)|Dorothy]]\n*[[Flora Cash]]\n*[[Larkin Poe]]\n*[[Brian Cadd]]\n*[[Ninet Tayeb]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n;August 17\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Dead & Company]]{{refn|group=nb|Dead & Company canceled their appearance on July 27.<ref name=\"rsdead\"/>}}\n*[[Chance the Rapper]]{{refn|group=nb|Chance the Rapper never formally canceled his appearance, but Woodstock 50 did not appear on his 2019 tour itinerary when dates were released on July 29.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Chance the Rapper tour dates include Buffalo concert; no Woodstock? |url=https://www.syracuse.com/celebrity-news/2019/07/chance-the-rapper-tour-dates-include-buffalo-concert-no-woodstock.html |website=syracuse.com |accessdate=31 July 2019 |date=29 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731232010/https://www.syracuse.com/celebrity-news/2019/07/chance-the-rapper-tour-dates-include-buffalo-concert-no-woodstock.html |archive-date=July 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>}}\n*[[The Black Keys]]{{refn|group=nb|The Black Keys canceled their appearance on April 5 due to a \"scheduling conflict\".<ref name=\"bk\"/>}}\n*[[Sturgill Simpson]]\n*[[Greta Van Fleet]]\n*[[Portugal. The Man]]\n*[[Leon Bridges]]\n*[[Gary Clark Jr.]]\n*[[Edward Sharpe and the Magnetic Zeros]]\n*[[David Crosby]] and Friends{{refn|group=nb|Crosby told ''Rolling Stone'' that he had canceled his appearance after the move to Vernon Downs was nixed, but did not make his cancelation public.<ref name=\"rs1\"/>}}\n*[[Dawes (band)|Dawes]]\n*[[Margo Price]]\n*[[Nahko and Medicine for the People]]\n*[[India.Arie]]\n*[[Jade Bird]]\n*[[Country Joe McDonald]]{{refn|group=nb|McDonald canceled his appearance on July 29.<ref name=\"sinkingship\"/>}}\n*[[Rival Sons]]\n*[[Emily King]]\n*[[Soccer Mommy]]\n*[[Sir (singer)|Sir]]\n*Taylor Bennett\n*[[Amy Helm]]\n*[[Courtney Hadwin]]\n*Pearl\n*John-Robert\n*IAMDDB\n{{Div col end}}\n\n;August 18\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Jay-Z]]{{refn|group=nb|Jay-Z officially canceled his appearance on July 26.<ref name=\"jayzpull\"/> Lang later stated that Jay-Z had privately canceled his performance after the festival lost its original Watkins Glen location.<ref name=\"rs1\"/>}}\n*[[Imagine Dragons]]\n*[[Halsey (singer)|Halsey]]\n*[[Cage the Elephant]]\n*[[Brandi Carlile]]\n*[[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]]\n*[[Young the Giant]]\n*[[Courtney Barnett]]\n*[[Common (rapper)|Common]]\n*[[Vince Staples]]\n*[[Judah & the Lion]]\n*[[Earl Sweatshirt]]\n*[[Boygenius]]\n*[[Reignwolf]]\n*[[The Zombies]]\n*[[Canned Heat]]\n*[[Hot Tuna]]\n*[[Pussy Riot]]{{refn|group=nb|Pussy Riot canceled their appearance on July 30.<ref name=\"raconteurs\"/>}}\n*[[Cherry Glazerr]]\n*[[Leven Kali]]\n*[[The Marcus King Band]]\n*[[Victory (band)|Victory]]\n*[[Hollis Brown (band)|Hollis Brown]]\n*[[John Craigie (musician)|John Craigie]]\n*Amigo the Devil\n*Liz Brasher\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Fyre Festival]], a similarly canceled music festival\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Woodstock}}\n\n[[Category:2019 in Maryland]]\n[[Category:2019 in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:2019 music festivals]]\n[[Category:Cancelled events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Cancelled music festivals]]\n[[Category:Woodstock Festival]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 planned American music festival}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use list-defined references|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox music festival\n| name         = Woodstock 50\n| image        = Woodstock 50 promotional poster.jpg\n| image_size   = \n| alt          = A poster listing the artists with a stylized dove resting on a globe\n| caption      = Original Woodstock 50 promotional poster\n| genre        = \n| dates        = August 16\u201318, 2019 (canceled)\n| location     = \n| coordinates  = \n| years_active = \n| founders     = [[Michael Lang (producer)|Michael Lang]]\n| attendance   = \n| capacity     = \n| website      = {{URL|woodstock.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Woodstock 50''' was a planned American music festival that was scheduled to be held on August 16\u201318, 2019, at [[Merriweather Post Pavilion]] in [[Columbia, Maryland]].<ref name=\"nysaved\">{{cite web |last1=Sisario |first1=Ben |title=Woodstock 50 Festival Is Saved, With Just Weeks to Spare |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/25/arts/music/woodstock-50-maryland.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=25 July 2019 |date=25 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725202841/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/25/arts/music/woodstock-50-maryland.html |archive-date=July 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The event was intended as a commemoration of the 50th anniversary of the [[Woodstock|Woodstock Music & Art Fair]], a landmark festival that was held on August 15\u201317, 1969, in [[Bethel, New York]].  Just prior to its cancellation, it was announced the event had been reduced from three days to one day.<ref name=\"varcyrus\"/> Woodstock 50 was canceled on July 31, 2019, after a series of permit and production issues, venue relocations, and artist cancellations.<ref name=\"w50rip\">{{cite web |last1=Halperin |first1=Shirley |title=Woodstock 50 Officially Off |url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/woodstock-50-off-dead-1203286874/ |website=Variety |accessdate=31 July 2019 |language=en |date=31 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731185730/https://variety.com/2019/music/news/woodstock-50-off-dead-1203286874/ |archive-date=July 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nArtists initially announced for the Woodstock 50 lineup included [[The Killers]], [[Imagine Dragons]], [[Halsey (singer)|Halsey]], [[Miley Cyrus]], [[Robert Plant]], [[The Raconteurs]], [[Cage the Elephant]] and [[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]]. The lineup also included several musical acts that had performed at [[Woodstock|the original 1969 festival]], such as [[Dead & Company]] (featuring three members of the [[Grateful Dead]]), [[John Fogerty]] (with [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]] in 1969), [[Santana (band)|Santana]], [[David Crosby (with [[Crosby, Stills & Nash]] in 1969]], [[Melanie (singer)|Melanie]], [[John Sebastian]], [[Hot Tuna]] (featuring two members of [[Jefferson Airplane]]), [[Canned Heat]] and [[Country Joe McDonald]] (lead singer of [[Country Joe and the Fish]] in 1969).<ref name=\"rs\">{{cite news |last1=Kreps |first1=Daniel |title=Woodstock 50 Details Full Lineup With Jay-Z, Dead & Company, Killers |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-details-full-lineup-with-jay-z-dead-company-killers-809290/ |accessdate=March 19, 2019 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=March 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320012256/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-details-full-lineup-with-jay-z-dead-company-killers-809290/ |archive-date=March 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWoodstock 50 and its lineup were officially announced in March 2019 but tickets were not released for sale on a previously scheduled date.<ref name=\"nytstock\"/> In late April 2019, a financial backer claimed the festival had been canceled, which was disputed by organizers.<ref name=\"cnnstock\"/> Conflicting media reports ranged from allegations of financial and legal difficulties to an inability to secure proper permits from local officials. In May, a judge ruled that the financiers had no right to cancel the festival, allowing the event to proceed as planned.<ref name=\"ShowGo\"/> The festival was to take place at the [[Watkins Glen International]] racetrack but in June 2019 the venue announced the event would no longer be held there.<ref name=\"watkinsgone\"/> The concert's location was moved to Merriweather Post Pavilion in Maryland on July 25.<ref name=\"bloom1\"/> The next day, all of the artists who had been initially announced as part of the festival's lineup were released from their contracts.<ref name=\"bblineup\"/>\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|Woodstock}}\n[[File:Cars drive through the Esses during the 2014 Sahlen's Six Hours of The Glen.jpg|thumb|right|Part of the [[Watkins Glen International]] racetrack (pictured in 2014), the original planned venue of the festival.]]\n\nWoodstock's co-creator [[Michael Lang (producer)|Michael Lang]] helped organize Woodstock 50.<ref name=\"ap\">{{cite web |url=https://www.apnews.com/05f5f20b964b4df8ad37e55d2a63eda3 |title=Festival co-founder: Lineup for Woodstock 50 coming soon |date=March 7, 2019 |publisher=[[AP News]] |last=Fekadu |first=Mesfin |access-date=March 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326112346/https://apnews.com/05f5f20b964b4df8ad37e55d2a63eda3 |archive-date=March 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lang had been planning to hold a 50th anniversary Woodstock festival in 2019 since at least 2014.<ref name=\"rs2014\">{{cite web |last1=Newman |first1=Jason |title=Woodstock Organizer Plots 50th Anniv. Concert |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-organizer-plotting-50th-anniversary-concert-for-2019-110421/ |website=Rolling Stone |date=30 May 2014}}</ref> He began negotiating with Japanese investment firm [[Dentsu Aegis Network]] in late 2018 to arrange funding for Woodstock 50.<ref name=\"rs1\">{{cite web |last1=Browne |first1=David |last2=Grow |first2=Kory |title=\u2018It Was One Problem After Another\u2019: How Woodstock 50 Turned Into a Disaster |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/woodstock-50-disaster-872320 |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=19 August 2019 |date=18 August 2019}}</ref> Lang was not a producer for the festival, and was instead hired as a consultant by Woodstock 50 LLC, a production company founded by hoteliers Greg Peck and Susan Cronin and a separate entity from Lang's company Woodstock Ventures.<ref name=\"rs1\"/> This arrangement was done so Lang could avoid a [[conflict of interest]] with Woodstock Ventures, which owns the rights to the Woodstock brand.<ref name=\"rs1\"/> Woodstock 50 LLC and Lang entered into a partnership with Dentsu Aegis in December 2018, and licensed the rights to use the Woodstock name from Woodstock Ventures.<ref name=\"rs1\"/> The investment firm was contracted to contribute about $49.1 million to fund the festival, based on Lang's initial estimated attendance number of 150,000 people.<ref name=\"rs1\"/>\n\nIn January 2019, Lang confirmed that he would be organizing a fourth three-day Woodstock festival that would take place in August in [[Watkins Glen, New York]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greene |first1=Andy |title=Three-Day Woodstock Festival From Original Organizer Coming This Summer |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50th-anniversary-michael-lang-775588/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 May 2019 |date=9 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414112739/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50th-anniversary-michael-lang-775588/ |archive-date=April 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Watkins Glen International]] racetrack was chosen as the location of the festival.<ref name=\"racetrack\">{{cite web |last1=Barry |first1=John W. |title=Watkins Glen International to host Woodstock anniversary show in August |url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2019/01/09/woodstock-watkins-glen-international/2524398002/ |website=The Poughkeepsie Journal |accessdate=6 May 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506183040/https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2019/01/09/woodstock-watkins-glen-international/2524398002/ |archive-date=May 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The site had previously hosted three large music festivals; [[Summer Jam at Watkins Glen]] in 1973 and two multi-day concerts organized by the rock band [[Phish]] in 2011 and 2015.<ref name=\"racetrack\"/> In August 2018, a third Phish festival scheduled to be held at the racetrack was canceled by [[New York Department of Health]] officials one day before it was scheduled to begin due to water quality and safety issues at the site following several days of flooding in the [[Finger Lakes]] region.<ref>{{cite web |title=Phish festival Curveball at Watkins Glen canceled over health concerns |url=https://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/2018/08/16/phish-festival-curveball-watkins-glen-canceled-over-health-concerns/1013358002/ |website=Rochester Democrat and Chronicle |accessdate=1 September 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Watkins Glen official: 'This whole valley kind of cleaned itself and went into Seneca Lake' |url=https://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/2018/08/17/phish-curveball-festival-watkins-glen-canceled-water-advisory/1018849002/ |website=Rochester Democrat and Chronicle |accessdate=1 September 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Lang said he planned for a separate water supply to be brought into the Woodstock 50 site to avoid the issues Phish had experienced.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Exclusive: How Woodstock 50 lineup was chosen, and how Watkins Glen won\u2019t repeat \u201999 disaster |url=https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/03/exclusive-how-woodstock-50-lineup-was-chosen-and-how-watkins-glen-wont-repeat-99-disaster.html |website=syracuse.com |accessdate=6 May 2019 |date=25 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506183043/https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/03/exclusive-how-woodstock-50-lineup-was-chosen-and-how-watkins-glen-wont-repeat-99-disaster.html |archive-date=May 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Billboard'' reported that promoters and agents for musical acts had tried to persuade Lang to seek another venue because the site was too far away from large hotels and was seen as a risky location to hold a festival following the circumstances of Phish's cancellation the previous year.<ref name=\"infighting\">{{cite web |last1=Brooks |first1=Dave |title=How Infighting and Delays Caused Woodstock 50 to Come Unwound |url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/legal-and-management/8510917/how-infighting-and-delays-caused-woodstock-50-to-come |website=Billboard |accessdate=11 May 2019 |date=10 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510202009/https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/legal-and-management/8510917/how-infighting-and-delays-caused-woodstock-50-to-come |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn selecting artists for the festival's lineup, Lang planned to book popular contemporary artists alongside musical acts who had appeared in lineup of the original 1969 Woodstock festival.<ref name=\"rs1\"/> In early documents, Lang named several potential headliners for Woodstock 50, including [[Lady Gaga]], [[Bruno Mars]], [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[My Morning Jacket]], [[Bruce Springsteen]], [[Stevie Wonder]], Phish, [[Kendrick Lamar]], [[Green Day]] and [[Drake (musician)|Drake]], none of whom would appear in the announced lineup.<ref name=\"rs1\"/> Lang had also sought [[Paul McCartney]], [[Billy Joel]] and a reunited [[Led Zeppelin]] as headlining performers, but with the exception of Led Zeppelin singer [[Robert Plant]], none of those artists appeared in Woodstock 50's final lineup.<ref name=\"infighting\"/> [[Joan Baez]] told ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' she had been approached to perform at the festival but had turned the offer down.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greene |first1=Andy |title=Joan Baez Reflects on the End of Her Farewell Tour and What\u2019s Next |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/joan-baez-interview-farewell-tour-rolling-thunder-trump-828142/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 May 2019 |date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190501053330/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/joan-baez-interview-farewell-tour-rolling-thunder-trump-828142/ |archive-date=May 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe festival's lineup was announced on March 19, 2019.<ref name=\"rslineup\">{{cite web |last1=Kreps |first1=Daniel |title=Woodstock 50 Details Full Lineup With Jay-Z, Dead & Company, Killers |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-details-full-lineup-with-jay-z-dead-company-killers-809290/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 May 2019 |date=19 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320012256/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-details-full-lineup-with-jay-z-dead-company-killers-809290/ |archive-date=March 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[The Black Keys]] were announced as part of the lineup but pulled out of the festival on April 5 due to a scheduling conflict.<ref name=\"bk\">{{cite web |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/04/the-black-keys-woodstock-canceled/ |title=The Black Keys pull out of Woodstock |date=April 5, 2019 |publisher=[[Consequence of Sound]] |last=Young |first=Alex |access-date=April 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406124735/https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/04/the-black-keys-woodstock-canceled/ |archive-date=April 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Black Keys drummer [[Patrick Carney]] later explained that the band decided to cancel because they had just returned from a hiatus, and \"We realized that we didn\u2019t want our first show back to be in front of 150,000 people in a field without any control.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pareles |first1=Jon |title=For the Black Keys, Rock Lives. It Just Had to Wait |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/27/arts/music/the-black-keys-lets-rock.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=19 August 2019 |date=27 June 2019}}</ref> Following the lineup announcement press conference, Dentsu Aegis privately expressed concern that organizers had spent too much money on acquiring artists other than those that had been previously considered.<ref name=\"rs1\"/>\n\nA second Woodstock 50th anniversary event, held at the [[Bethel Woods Center for the Arts]]\u2014the site of the original 1969 festival\u2014was also scheduled for August 2019. The lineup for the three-day concert program included John Fogerty and Santana, both of whom were included in the Woodstock 50 lineup, as well as [[Ringo Starr]], [[Arlo Guthrie]], [[Edgar Winter]], [[the Doobie Brothers]], [[Blood, Sweat & Tears]], [[Tedeschi Trucks Band]] and [[Grace Potter]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Bethel Woods finalizes Woodstock anniversary weekend lineup |url=https://www.syracuse.com/celebrity-news/2019/04/bethel-woods-finalizes-woodstock-anniversary-weekend-lineup.html |website=syracuse.com |accessdate=7 May 2019 |date=25 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502214911/https://www.syracuse.com/celebrity-news/2019/04/bethel-woods-finalizes-woodstock-anniversary-weekend-lineup.html |archive-date=May 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"bethel1\">{{cite web |title=Bethel Woods Celebrates Woodstock's 50th Anniversary with Santana, John Fogerty, Ringo Starr, Tedeschi Trucks Band and More |url=https://jambands.com/news/2019/08/19/bethel-woods-celebrates-woodstocks-50th-anniversary-with-santana-john-fogerty-ringo-starr-tedeschi-trucks-band-and-more/ |website=Jambands |accessdate=13 September 2019 |date=19 August 2019}}</ref> Lang was not involved with the Bethel concert and filed a cease-and-desist notice against its organizer [[Live Nation (events promoter)|Live Nation]] for promoting it as a rival event to his Woodstock 50 festival.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Urken |first1=Ross |title=Woodstock Backers Hope to Export Brand to Other Countries |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-04-23/woodstock-backers-hope-to-export-brand-to-other-countries |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=7 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507032817/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-04-23/woodstock-backers-hope-to-export-brand-to-other-countries |archive-date=May 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Bethel concerts were held as planned on August 16\u201318.<ref name=\"bethel1\"/>\n\n==Production issues==\n\n===Ticketing and permit delays===\nTickets for the Woodstock 50 festival were supposed to go on sale on April 22, 2019, but no tickets were made available on that date.<ref name=\"nytstock\">{{cite web |last1=Sisario |first1=Ben |title=Woodstock 50\u2019s Backer Says the Festival Is Off. Its Promoter Is Holding Out Hope. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/29/arts/music/woodstock-50th-anniversary-canceled.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=29 April 2019 |date=29 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430025214/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/29/arts/music/woodstock-50th-anniversary-canceled.html |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> At that date, the organizers had yet to receive a mass gathering permit from the New York State Department of Health.<ref>{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 Ticket Sales Delayed as Organizers Lack Required Permit |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/woodstock-50-ticket-sales-delayed-as-organizers-lack-required-permit/ |website=Pitchfork |accessdate=29 April 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430032334/https://pitchfork.com/news/woodstock-50-ticket-sales-delayed-as-organizers-lack-required-permit/ |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> A New York state health regulation forbids advertising for large, overnights events that do not have a permit, which delayed the sale of tickets.<ref name=\"rs1\"/> A mass gathering permit for the festival had been submitted on April 15 but the Department of Health had not approved it at that time.<ref name=\"syra2\"/>\n\n===First cancellation and change of investors===\n\nOn April 29, investors [[Dentsu Aegis Network]], which had been funding Woodstock 50 through its subsidiary Amplifi Live, announced it was no longer funding the festival and that the event had been canceled.<ref>{{cite web |title=Woodstock Organizers Cancel 50th Anniversary Festival |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/festivals/8509091/woodstock-50-festival-cancelled |website=Billboard |accessdate=29 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190429173706/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/festivals/8509091/woodstock-50-festival-cancelled |archive-date=April 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Officials from [[Schuyler County, New York]] also confirmed the cancellation.<ref name=\"cnnstock\">{{cite web |last1=Kaur |first1=Harmeet |title=The Woodstock 50 festival might be canceled, but also it might not be |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/29/entertainment/woodstock-50-festival-canceled-trnd/ |website=CNN |accessdate=29 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430032237/https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/29/entertainment/woodstock-50-festival-canceled-trnd/ |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Dentsu Aegis ceased its involvement after the organizers reduced the capacity of the festival grounds from 100,000 people to 75,000 to accommodate campers after initially promising the company a crowd of 150,000.<ref name=\"syracuse1\">{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Woodstock 50 artists won\u2019t perform; organizer hires Trump attorney (reports) |url=https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/05/woodstock-50-artists-wont-perform-organizer-hires-trump-attorney-reports.html |website=syracuse.com |accessdate=2 May 2019 |date=2 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502214658/https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/05/woodstock-50-artists-wont-perform-organizer-hires-trump-attorney-reports.html |archive-date=May 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later that day, the festival organizers disputed the cancellation in a statement to the ''[[Poughkeepsie Journal]]'' and announced they would be seeking a \"legal remedy\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Has Woodstock 50 been canceled? Organizers argue over status |url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2019/04/29/woodstock-50-cancellation-argument/3616705002/ |website=The Poughkeepsie Journal |accessdate=29 April 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190429192632/https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2019/04/29/woodstock-50-cancellation-argument/3616705002/ |archive-date=April 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On the same day, Lang stated on his Facebook page that, despite the loss of their financial backer, the Woodstock 50 organizers would continue to plan the festival and would seek new investors, and the festival would go ahead as planned.{{refn|group=nb|Michael Lang: \"We are committed to ensuring that the 50th anniversary of Woodstock is marked with a festival deserving of its iconic name and place in American history and culture. Although our financial partner is withdrawing, we will of course be continuing with the planning of the festival and intend to bring on new partners. We would like to acknowledge the State of New York and Schuyler County for all of their hard work and support. The bottom line is, there is going to be a Woodstock 50th Anniversary Festival, as there must be, and it\u2019s going to be a blast!\"}}<ref name=\"jambase.com Woodstock 50 not canceled\">{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 Organizer Michael Lang Says Festival Not Canceled |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/woodstock-50-not-canceled |website=JamBase |accessdate=30 April 2019 |date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430135853/https://www.jambase.com/article/woodstock-50-not-canceled |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Superfly (company)|Superfly]], a production partner of the Woodstock organizers, pulled out of the festival on May 1.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Grow |first1=Kory |title=Woodstock 50 Loses Production Partner Superfly, Putting Festival in Jeopardy |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-loses-superfly-829577/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 May 2019 |date=1 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190501193011/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-loses-superfly-829577/ |archive-date=May 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Superfly also cited changes to the festival's capacity as a reason for its withdrawal.<ref name=\"infighting\"/> Before departing the project, Superfly had estimated  65,000 people as the safest maximum capacity for the festival at Watkins Glen, which was a lower estimate than either Dentsu Aegis or Lang had previously considered.<ref name=\"rs1\"/> Once they received better information of the terrain on the race-track property, they had revised their maximum capacity estimate to 61,000, and stated they would not continue to work on the festival if any planning went ahead for a capacity above that number.<ref name=\"rs1\"/>\n\nAs result of Dentsu Aegis's withdrawal, none of the artists on the lineup were obliged to play at the event because they had made payment agreements through either Dentsu or Amplifi Live rather than the Woodstock promoters.<ref name=\"syracuse1\"/><ref name=\"billboard1\">{{cite web |title=Woodstock Founder Michael Lang Vows Show Will Go On -- But Talent Agencies Say Artists Won't Play |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/8509483/michael-lang-save-woodstock-booking-artists-funding-contracts-agencies |website=Billboard |accessdate=2 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190501215153/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/8509483/michael-lang-save-woodstock-booking-artists-funding-contracts-agencies |archive-date=May 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Representatives from two major talent agencies told ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Dentsu Aegis' decision may have voided the artists' contracts and it was unlikely their clients would be performing at the festival.<ref name=\"billboard1\"/> Following the company's announcement, Dead & Company removed Woodstock 50 from the tour itinerary on their website.<ref>{{cite web |title=John Fogerty Talks Woodstock 50 Potential Cancellation |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/john-fogerty-woodstock-50-cancellation |website=JamBase |accessdate=30 April 2019 |date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430210410/https://www.jambase.com/article/john-fogerty-woodstock-50-cancellation |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> John Fogerty told ''Rolling Stone'' he was disappointed by the announcement and surprised the festival had not secured permits sooner, saying. \"You got the sense there was some shakiness to this whole thing\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Browne |first1=David |title=John Fogerty on Woodstock 50: \u2018There Was Some Shakiness to This Whole Thing\u2019 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/john-fogerty-woodstock-50-cancellation-828793/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=30 April 2019 |date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430210409/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/john-fogerty-woodstock-50-cancellation-828793/ |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''Billboard'' reported on May 6 that CID Entertainment would be producing the festival and that for the event to proceed, Lang would have needed about $30 million by May 10 and a mass gathering permit from the New York Department of Health.<ref>{{cite web |title=To Save Woodstock 50, Michael Lang Plans to Raise $30M by Friday |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8510342/woodstock-50-michael-lang-raise-30m-by-friday-save-festival |website=Billboard |accessdate=7 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506234332/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8510342/woodstock-50-michael-lang-raise-30m-by-friday-save-festival |archive-date=May 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lang also accused Dentsu Aegis of illegally removing $17 million from the festival's bank account, blocking the April 22 ticket sale and attempting to cancel the event without his consent.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Willman |first1=Chris |title=Woodstock Founder Says Japanese Investors Siphoned $17 Million, Sinking Festival |url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/woodstock-founder-michael-lang-claims-investors-dentsu-17-million-1203206596/ |website=Variety |accessdate=7 May 2019 |language=en |date=6 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507022236/https://variety.com/2019/music/news/woodstock-founder-michael-lang-claims-investors-dentsu-17-million-1203206596/ |archive-date=May 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lawyers for the Woodstock organizers requested an injunction against Dentsu Aegis in a New York court on May 9, seeking the return of the disputed $17 million.<ref name=\"injunct\">{{cite web |last1=Browne |first1=David |last2=Grow |first2=Kory |title=Woodstock 50\u2019s Last Stand: 6 Key Things We Learned From New Court Papers |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-dentsu-court-papers-833666/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=11 May 2019 |date=10 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511024436/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-dentsu-court-papers-833666/ |archive-date=May 11, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Amplifi Live filed a counter-claim against Lang on May 13, arguing they had the right to take over the festival and cancel it due to Lang's contractual breaches and logistical misrepresentation.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Grow |first1=Kory |title=\u2018Incompetence and Contractual Breaches.\u2019 Dentsu Fires Back at Woodstock Organizers |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-dentsu-aegis-amplifi-live-response-834737/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=13 May 2019 |date=13 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513230539/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-dentsu-aegis-amplifi-live-response-834737/ |archive-date=May 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA judge in [[New York Supreme Court]] ruled in favor of the Woodstock organizers on May 15 and found that Dentsu Aegis had no legal right to cancel the festival, allowing the event to proceed.<ref name=\"ShowGo\">{{cite web |last1=Browne |first1=David |title=Woodstock 50: The Show Will Go On, But New Funding Needed |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-dentsu-court-decision-835976/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=15 May 2019 |date=15 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516024503/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/woodstock-50-dentsu-court-decision-835976/ |archive-date=May 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The judge also ruled that the organizers were not entitled to the $17.8 million that had been removed from the festival's bank account.<ref name=\"ShowGo\"/> On May 17, [[Oppenheimer Holdings]] was announced as the festival's new financial backer.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bloom |first1=Madison |title=Woodstock 50 Gets New Investors |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/woodstock-50-gets-new-investors/ |website=Pitchfork |accessdate=17 May 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517220126/https://pitchfork.com/news/woodstock-50-gets-new-investors/ |archive-date=May 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Following the court ruling, Lang announced that three-day passes to the festival would cost around $400 and that a limited quantity of limited single-day passes would be available, a change from earlier plans in which only three-day passes would be sold.<ref name=\"syra2\">{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Woodstock 50 tickets will be less than $400, organizer now says |url=https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/05/woodstock-50-tickets-will-be-less-than-400-organizer-now-says.html |website=syracuse.com |accessdate=17 May 2019 |date=17 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517153307/https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/05/woodstock-50-tickets-will-be-less-than-400-organizer-now-says.html |archive-date=May 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Loss of original venue===\nWatkins Glen International announced on June 10 it had canceled the contract for the Woodstock 50 festival and that the event would no longer be held at the racetrack.<ref name=\"watkinsgone\">{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 loses site: Watkins Glen racetrack says it won't host |url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2019/06/10/woodstock-50-loses-site-watkins-glen-racetrack-says-wont-host/1413072001/ |website=The Poughkeepsie Journal |accessdate=10 June 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610232115/https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2019/06/10/woodstock-50-loses-site-watkins-glen-racetrack-says-wont-host/1413072001/ |archive-date=June 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The festival had lost its booking at the racetrack because organizers had missed a $150,000 payment.<ref>{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 lost Watkins Glen site after missing $150k payment |url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/entertainment/2019/06/13/woodstock-50-lost-watkins-glen-site-because-missed-150-k-payment/1445880001/ |website=The Poughkeepsie Journal |accessdate=15 June 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190614000842/https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/entertainment/2019/06/13/woodstock-50-lost-watkins-glen-site-because-missed-150-k-payment/1445880001/ |archive-date=June 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The same day, CID Entertainment announced it would also be pulling out of the festival.<ref>{{cite web |title=Second Woodstock 50 Producer Pulls Out After Festival Loses Site |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8515238/woodstock-50-festival-loses-site-producer-cid-entertainment-pulls-out |website=Billboard |accessdate=10 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190611010154/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8515238/woodstock-50-festival-loses-site-producer-cid-entertainment-pulls-out |archive-date=June 11, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> A representative for the festival subsequently told [[Associated Press]] the organizers were in talks with another venue to host the event.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Payne |first1=The Associated Press and Ed |title=Woodstock 50 in doubt: Organizers in talks with another venue |url=https://www.wowt.com/content/news/Woodstock-50-in-doubt-Organizers-in-talks-with-another-venue-511130832.html |website=www.wowt.com |accessdate=12 June 2019 |language=english |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190612033427/https://www.wowt.com/content/news/Woodstock-50-in-doubt-Organizers-in-talks-with-another-venue-511130832.html |archive-date=June 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn late June, the Woodstock organizers applied for a permit to hold a smaller festival at [[Vernon Downs]] horse racing track in [[Vernon, New York]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Woodstock 50 applies for permit at Vernon Downs; up to 65,000 expected (reports) |url=https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/06/woodstock-50-applies-for-permit-at-vernon-downs-up-to-65000-expected-reports.html |website=syracuse.com |accessdate=27 June 2019 |date=26 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190627171701/https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/06/woodstock-50-applies-for-permit-at-vernon-downs-up-to-65000-expected-reports.html |archive-date=June 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The organizers were refused the permit on July 9.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aswad |first1=Jem |title=Woodstock 50 Permit Denied by Latest Proposed Site |url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/woodstock-50-permit-denied-1203262790/ |website=Variety |accessdate=9 July 2019 |language=en |date=9 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709214702/https://variety.com/2019/music/news/woodstock-50-permit-denied-1203262790/ |archive-date=July 9, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The organizers' third appeal was denied by the Vernon planning board on July 16.<ref>{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 Loses Third Appeal In New York\u2019s Vernon |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2051418/woodstock-50-loses-third-appeal-in-new-yorks-vernon/news/ |website=Stereogum |accessdate=20 July 2019 |date=16 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720162404/https://www.stereogum.com/2051418/woodstock-50-loses-third-appeal-in-new-yorks-vernon/news/ |archive-date=July 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Following the ruling, Lang said he would not sue the town to force it to host the event and conceded that the festival would not be held at Vernon Downs.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Woodstock 50 \u2018considering all options\u2019 after CNY town says no |url=https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/07/woodstock-50-considering-all-options-after-cny-town-says-no.html |website=syracuse.com |accessdate=20 July 2019 |date=18 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720162406/https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/07/woodstock-50-considering-all-options-after-cny-town-says-no.html |archive-date=July 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Relocation to Maryland and loss of artist lineup===\n[[File:Merriweather Post Pavilion.jpg|thumb|The festival was to be held at the [[Merriweather Post Pavilion]] (pictured in 2017) in [[Columbia, Maryland]].]]\n\n''[[Bloomberg News]]'' reported on July 25 that the Woodstock organizers had moved the festival to [[Merriweather Post Pavilion]], a venue with a smaller capacity than either of the planned New York sites, in [[Columbia, Maryland]].<ref name=\"bloom1\">{{cite web |last1=Shaw |first1=Lucas |title=Woodstock 50 Festival Moves to Maryland in Bid to Salvage Event |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-25/woodstock-50-festival-moves-to-maryland-in-bid-to-salvage-event |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=25 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725202424/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-25/woodstock-50-festival-moves-to-maryland-in-bid-to-salvage-event |archive-date=July 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Known as \"Woodstock 50 Washington\", the festival would act as a fundraiser for non-profit organizations involved with [[Voter registration campaign|voter registration]] and [[climate change]].<ref name=\"bloom1\"/> Instead of being a ticketed event as originally planned, the festival would be free and concertgoers would  be encouraged to donate to charitable causes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 (Now In Maryland And Without A Lineup) Will Reportedly Be Free |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2052824/woodstock-50-maryland-free/news/ |website=Stereogum |accessdate=27 July 2019 |date=27 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727192016/https://www.stereogum.com/2052824/woodstock-50-maryland-free/news/ |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Seth Hurwitz, co-founder of Merriweather Post Pavilion operator IMP, said his venue would host the festival if organizers presented them with a lineup.<ref name=\"raconteurs\">{{cite web |last1=Newman |first1=Jason |title=The Raconteurs Drop Out of Woodstock 50 as Maryland Still Awaits Permit Application |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-raconteurs-drop-out-woodstock-50-865159/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=30 July 2019 |date=30 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730203611/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-raconteurs-drop-out-woodstock-50-865159/ |archive-date=July 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> A concert headlined by [[The Smashing Pumpkins]] was scheduled to take place at the venue on August 17.<ref>{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 Reportedly Plotting Move To Merriweather Post Pavilion |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/woodstock-50-merriweather-post-pavilion |website=JamBase |accessdate=25 July 2019 |date=25 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725201258/https://www.jambase.com/article/woodstock-50-merriweather-post-pavilion |archive-date=July 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Woodstock 50 would have been reduced from three days to one.<ref name=\"varcyrus\">{{cite web |last1=Aswad |first1=Jem |last2=Halperin |first2=Shirley |title=Miley Cyrus Pulls Out of Woodstock 50 |url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/woodstock-50-one-day-event-common-akon-zombies-1203282632/ |website=Variety |accessdate=31 July 2019 |language=en |date=30 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731000603/https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/woodstock-50-one-day-event-common-akon-zombies-1203282632/ |archive-date=July 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Jay-Z]] and John Fogerty withdrew from the Woodstock 50 lineup shortly after the move to Maryland was announced.<ref name=\"jayzpull\">{{cite web |last1=Nyren |first1=Erin |title=Jay-Z Pulls Out of Woodstock 50 |url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/jay-z-pulls-out-of-woodstock-50-1203281030/ |website=variety.com |accessdate=26 July 2019 |date=26 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726163950/https://variety.com/2019/music/news/jay-z-pulls-out-of-woodstock-50-1203281030/ |archive-date=July 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  On July 26, the promoters released all of the remaining artists on the lineup from their contracted appearances at the relocated festival.<ref name=\"bblineup\">{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 Releases All Artists From Contracts After Maryland Announcement |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/8523989/woodstock-50-releases-all-artists-lineup-maryland-move-venue |website=Billboard |accessdate=26 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726184911/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/8523989/woodstock-50-releases-all-artists-lineup-maryland-move-venue |archive-date=July 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The organizers informed artists of the relocation and contract release in a letter that also requested they still perform at the festival and reminded them of the payment they had received from Dentsu Aegis.<ref name=\"finaldays\">{{cite web |last1=Brooks |first1=Dave |title=Inside the Final Days of Woodstock 50 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/8525668/woodstock-50-final-days-artists-pulling-out-maryland |website=Billboard |accessdate=31 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801023326/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/8525668/woodstock-50-final-days-artists-pulling-out-maryland |archive-date=August 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the following days, Dead & Company, Country Joe McDonald, John Sebastian, Santana, [[The Lumineers]], [[The Raconteurs]], [[Pussy Riot]] and [[Miley Cyrus]] announced they would not be appearing at the relocated festival.<ref name=\"rsdead\">{{cite web |last1=Newman |first1=Jason |title=Dead & Company Drop Out of Woodstock 50 as Artists Flee Beleaguered Festival |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dead-and-co-woodstock-50-864297/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=27 July 2019 |date=26 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727154930/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dead-and-co-woodstock-50-864297/ |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"sinkingship\">{{cite web |last1=Reed |first1=Ryan |title=Woodstock \u201969 Vet Country Joe McDonald Leaps Off \u2018Sinking Ship\u2019 Woodstock 50 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/country-joe-mcdonald-john-sebastian-woodstock-50-865039/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=30 July 2019 |date=30 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730034814/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/country-joe-mcdonald-john-sebastian-woodstock-50-865039/ |archive-date=July 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"raconteurs\"/><ref name=\"varcyrus\"/> Several artists withdrew because they had already scheduled other concerts in the [[Mid-Atlantic (United States)|Mid-Atlantic]] region around the festival weekend and the relocation to Merriweather Post Pavilion conflicted with the [[radius clause]]s for some of those events.<ref name=\"finaldays\"/> A representative for [[The Zombies]] told ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' that the band still planned to perform at Woodstock 50.<ref name=\"varcyrus\"/> On July 30, 17 days before the festival's planned start date, Woodstock 50 organizers had not submitted a permit application to hold an event at Merriweather Post Pavilion.<ref name=\"raconteurs\"/>\n\n===Final cancellation===\nOn July 31, the organizers of Woodstock 50 announced the cancellation of the event.<ref name=\"w50rip\"/> In a press release, representatives said, \"unforeseen setbacks made it impossible to put on a festival we imagined with the great line-up we had booked and the social engagement we were anticipating\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Woodstock 50 Is Officially Canceled |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/woodstock-50-is-officially-canceled/ |website=Pitchfork |accessdate=31 July 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731190125/https://pitchfork.com/news/woodstock-50-is-officially-canceled/ |archive-date=July 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lang told media he blamed Dentsu Aegis for the festival's failure and that he was considering further legal action against the firm.<ref name=\"langsyr\">{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Woodstock 50 organizer blames everyone else for canceled festival |url=https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2019/08/woodstock-50-organizer-blames-everyone-else-for-canceled-festival.html |website=syracuse.com |accessdate=1 August 2019 |date=1 August 2019}}</ref> Despite the cancellation, Lang said he hoped to hold a smaller fundraising event at Merriweather Post Pavilion in late 2019 but was not sure it would bear the Woodstock name.<ref name=\"langsyr\"/>\n\n==Planned line-up==\nEach artist on the Woodstock 50 lineup was paid an advance and the remainder of the payment was held in [[escrow]] until performance or the cancellation of the festival. Alongside the official announcement that the event would not proceed, the organizers suggested the artists donate at least 10 percent of their earnings to [[HeadCount]], a non-profit organization that promotes voter registration. Lang was criticized for trying to make the artists feel guilty.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/woodstock-50-artists-to-receive-millions-despite-cancellation-1203288655/ |title=Woodstock 50 Artists to Receive Millions Despite Festival Cancellation |last=Aswad |first=Shirley Halperin,Jem |last2=Halperin |first2=Shirley |date=2019-08-01 |website=Variety |language=en |access-date=2019-08-15 |last3=Aswad |first3=Jem}}</ref> Prior to July 26, 2019, when remaining artists withdrew ''en masse'' from the event and organizers released them from their contracts,<ref name=\"bblineup\"/> the lineup for the festival was to have included:<ref name=\"rslineup\"/>\n\n;August 16\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[The Killers]]\n*[[Miley Cyrus]]{{refn|group=nb|Cyrus canceled her appearance on July 30.<ref name=\"raconteurs\"/>}}\n*[[Santana (band)|Santana]]{{refn|group=nb|Santana canceled their appearance on July 30.<ref name=\"santana\">{{cite web |last1=Bary |first1=John |title=Woodstock 50: Santana, Lumineers, Raconteurs drop out |url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/2019/07/30/woodstock-50-santana-drop-out/1867203001/ |website=The Poughkeepsie Journal |accessdate=1 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref>}}\n*[[The Lumineers]]{{refn|group=nb|The Lumineers canceled their appearance on July 30.<ref name=\"raconteurs\"/>}}\n*[[The Raconteurs]]{{refn|group=nb|The Raconteurs canceled their appearance on July 30.<ref name=\"raconteurs\"/>}}\n*[[Robert Plant]] and the Sensational Space Shifters\n*[[Nathaniel Rateliff]] and the Night Sweats\n*[[John Fogerty]]{{refn|group=nb|Fogerty canceled his appearance on July 25.<ref name=\"jayzpull\"/>}}\n*[[Run the Jewels]]\n*[[The Head and the Heart]]\n*[[Maggie Rogers]]\n*[[Michael Franti & Spearhead]]\n*[[Bishop Briggs]]\n*[[Anderson East]]\n*[[Akon]]\n*[[Princess Nokia]]\n*[[John Sebastian]]{{refn|group=nb|Sebastian canceled his appearance on July 29.<ref name=\"sinkingship\"/>}}\n*[[Melanie (singer)|Melanie]]\n*[[Grandson (musician)|Grandson]]\n*[[Fever 333]]\n*[[Dorothy (band)|Dorothy]]\n*[[Flora Cash]]\n*[[Larkin Poe]]\n*[[Brian Cadd]]\n*[[Ninet Tayeb]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n;August 17\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Dead & Company]]{{refn|group=nb|Dead & Company canceled their appearance on July 27.<ref name=\"rsdead\"/>}}\n*[[Chance the Rapper]]{{refn|group=nb|Chance the Rapper never formally canceled his appearance, but Woodstock 50 did not appear on his 2019 tour itinerary when dates were released on July 29.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Chance the Rapper tour dates include Buffalo concert; no Woodstock? |url=https://www.syracuse.com/celebrity-news/2019/07/chance-the-rapper-tour-dates-include-buffalo-concert-no-woodstock.html |website=syracuse.com |accessdate=31 July 2019 |date=29 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731232010/https://www.syracuse.com/celebrity-news/2019/07/chance-the-rapper-tour-dates-include-buffalo-concert-no-woodstock.html |archive-date=July 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>}}\n*[[The Black Keys]]{{refn|group=nb|The Black Keys canceled their appearance on April 5 due to a \"scheduling conflict\".<ref name=\"bk\"/>}}\n*[[Sturgill Simpson]]\n*[[Greta Van Fleet]]\n*[[Portugal. The Man]]\n*[[Leon Bridges]]\n*[[Gary Clark Jr.]]\n*[[Edward Sharpe and the Magnetic Zeros]]\n*[[David Crosby]] and Friends{{refn|group=nb|Crosby told ''Rolling Stone'' that he had canceled his appearance after the move to Vernon Downs was nixed, but did not make his cancelation public.<ref name=\"rs1\"/>}}\n*[[Dawes (band)|Dawes]]\n*[[Margo Price]]\n*[[Nahko and Medicine for the People]]\n*[[India.Arie]]\n*[[Jade Bird]]\n*[[Country Joe McDonald]]{{refn|group=nb|McDonald canceled his appearance on July 29.<ref name=\"sinkingship\"/>}}\n*[[Rival Sons]]\n*[[Emily King]]\n*[[Soccer Mommy]]\n*[[Sir (singer)|Sir]]\n*Taylor Bennett\n*[[Amy Helm]]\n*[[Courtney Hadwin]]\n*Pearl\n*John-Robert\n*IAMDDB\n{{Div col end}}\n\n;August 18\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Jay-Z]]{{refn|group=nb|Jay-Z officially canceled his appearance on July 26.<ref name=\"jayzpull\"/> Lang later stated that Jay-Z had privately canceled his performance after the festival lost its original Watkins Glen location.<ref name=\"rs1\"/>}}\n*[[Imagine Dragons]]\n*[[Halsey (singer)|Halsey]]\n*[[Cage the Elephant]]\n*[[Brandi Carlile]]\n*[[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]]\n*[[Young the Giant]]\n*[[Courtney Barnett]]\n*[[Common (rapper)|Common]]\n*[[Vince Staples]]\n*[[Judah & the Lion]]\n*[[Earl Sweatshirt]]\n*[[Boygenius]]\n*[[Reignwolf]]\n*[[The Zombies]]\n*[[Canned Heat]]\n*[[Hot Tuna]]\n*[[Pussy Riot]]{{refn|group=nb|Pussy Riot canceled their appearance on July 30.<ref name=\"raconteurs\"/>}}\n*[[Cherry Glazerr]]\n*[[Leven Kali]]\n*[[The Marcus King Band]]\n*[[Victory (band)|Victory]]\n*[[Hollis Brown (band)|Hollis Brown]]\n*[[John Craigie (musician)|John Craigie]]\n*Amigo the Devil\n*Liz Brasher\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Fyre Festival]], a similarly canceled music festival\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Woodstock}}\n\n[[Category:2019 in Maryland]]\n[[Category:2019 in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:2019 music festivals]]\n[[Category:Cancelled events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Cancelled music festivals]]\n[[Category:Woodstock Festival]]\n", "name_user": "No Great Shaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOverview:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woodstock_50"}
{"title_page": "Parable of a scribe", "text_new": "The '''Parable of a scribe''' is one of the [[Parables of Jesus]]. It appears in the [[Gospel of Matthew]], chapter 13, verses 51-53.<ref>https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Matthew+13&version=NKJV</ref> This parable is as follows: \"Then He said to them, \u201cTherefore every scribe instructed concerning the kingdom of heaven is like a householder who brings out of his treasure things new and old.\"[[New King James Version]].\n\n==Interpretation==\nThis parable is the final one in the chapter of Matthew 13. It tells of a [[Jews|Jew]] or a Hebrew [[Scribe]] who is converted to [[Christianity]]. This parable, like the rest of the parables in Matthew 13, describes the Kingdom of Heaven as the Church or the body of Christ. Here an [[Old Testament]] scribe who is converted to Christianity is compared to a house owner who brings out old and new things from his household. As we can understand from the passage, the scribe is the house owner. The difficulty is around the phrase \"new and old\". This can be interpreted as the new and old testaments in the [[bible]]. As a scribe who rewrites the [[Torah]] knows it better than anyone, so when he became a disciple of the [[New Testament]] or the teachings of [[Jesus]], he will be able teach from both the old and new testaments. This parable also gives a hint that studying the old testament only would not make a person to go to heaven. If one longs to be a true Christian he needs to study the new testament also.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n{{Parables of Jesus|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Gospel of Matthew]]\n[[Category:Parables of Jesus|Scribe]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Parable of a scribe''' is one of the [[Parables of Jesus]]. It appears in the [[Gospel of Matthew]], chapter 13, verses 51-53.<ref>https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Matthew+13&version=NKJV</ref> This parable is as follows: \"Then He said to them, \u201cTherefore every scribe instructed concerning the kingdom of heaven is like a householder who brings out of his treasure things new and old.\"[[New King James Version]].\n\n==Interpretation==\nThis parable is the final one in the chapter of Matthew 13. It tells of a [[Jews|Jew]] or a Hebrew [[Scribe]] who is converted to [[Christianity]]. This parable, like the rest of the parables in Matthew 13, describes the Kingdom of Heaven as the Church or the body of Christ. Here an [[Old Testament]] scribe who is converted to Christianity is compared to a house owner who brings out old and new things from his household. As we can understand from the passage, the scribe is the house owner. The difficulty is around the phrase \"new and old\". This can be interpreted as the new and old testaments in the [[bible]]. As a scribe who rewrites the [[Torah]] knows it better than anyone, so when he became a disciple of the [[new testament]] or the teachings of [[Jesus]], he will be able teach from both the old and new testaments. This parable also gives a hint that studying the old testament only would not make a person to go to heaven. If one longs to be a true Christian he needs to study the new testament also.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n{{Parables of Jesus|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Gospel of Matthew]]\n[[Category:Parables of Jesus|Scribe]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling correction; redirect bypass fromNew testamenttoNew Testamentusingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parable_of_a_scribe"}
{"title_page": "\u00centorsura Buz\u0103ului", "text_new": "{{morerefs|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Covasna\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Covasna County\n|subdivisions           = \n|official_name=\u00centorsura Buz\u0103ului\n|image_skyline=Panorama_intorsura_buzaului_covasna_romania.jpg\n|image_shield=ROU CV Intorsura Buzaului CoA1.jpg\n|image_map=Intorsatura Buzaului jud Covasna.png\n|coordinates      = {{coord|45|40|22|N|26|2|3|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|leader_party=ALDE\n|leader_name=Leca B\u0103ncil\u0103<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|area_total_km2=60\n|website={{url|http://www.intorsura.info/}}\n}}\n'''\u00centorsura Buz\u0103ului''' ({{lang-hu|Bodzafordul\u00f3}} {{IPA-hu|\u02c8bodd\u0361z\u0252fordulo\u02d0||Bodzafordul\u00f3.ogg}}) is  a town in [[Covasna County]], [[Transylvania]], [[Romania]]. It administers three villages: Br\u0103det (''Bred\u00e9t''), Floroaia (''Vir\u00e1gospatak'') and Scr\u0103doasa.\n\n== Population ==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1977 |6541\n|1992 |8626\n|2002 |9081\n|2011 |7319\n}}\n\nAt the 2011 Romanian census, the town had 7319 inhabitants, of whom 7265 were [[Romanians]], 37 were [[Hungarian people|Hungarians]], and 12 [[Romani people|Romani]].<ref>[http://www.edrc.ro/recensamant.jsp?regiune_id=2568&judet_id=2699&localitate_id=2704 2002 Census data for \u00centorsura Buz\u0103ului]</ref>\n\n''Demographic movement according to the censuses:''\n<timeline>\nColors=\n  id:lightgrey value:gray(0.9)\n  id:darkgrey  value:gray(0.7)\n  id:sfondo value:rgb(1,1,1)\n  id:barra value:rgb(0.6,0.7,0.8)\n\nImageSize  = width:280 height:220\nPlotArea   = left:50 bottom:50 top:30 right:30\nDateFormat = x.y\nPeriod     = from:0 till:9000\nTimeAxis   = orientation:vertical\nAlignBars  = justify\nScaleMajor = gridcolor:darkgrey increment:1000 start:0\nScaleMinor = gridcolor:lightgrey increment:250 start:0\nBackgroundColors = canvas:sfondo\nBarData=\n  bar:1977 text:1977\n  bar:1992 text:1992\n  bar:2002 text:2002\nPlotData=\n  color:barra width:20 align:left\n  bar:1977 from:0 till: 6541\n  bar:1992 from:0 till: 8626\n  bar:2002 from:0 till: 8926\nPlotData=\n  bar:1977 at: 6541 fontsize:S text: 6.541 shift:(-7,5)\n  bar:1992 at: 8626 fontsize:S text: 8.626 shift:(-11,5)\n  bar:2002 at: 8926 fontsize:S text: 8.926 shift:(-13,5)\nTextData=\n  fontsize:S pos:(20,20)\n  text:Census Data. Graphics made by Ro Wikipedia.\n</timeline>\n\n== Geography and climate ==\n\nThe town is located at 750m altitude, in a depression, surrounded by \u00centorsurii, Ciuca\u0219 and Siriu mountains. Due to its location, \u00centorsura Buz\u0103ului registers the lowest temperatures in Romania every year.{{fact|date=January 2020}} \n\nThe town is located on national road DN 10 that links Bra\u0219ov to Buz\u0103u. This road passes through the [[Carpathian Mountains]] and most of its length follows the Buz\u0103u River. There is also a rail road that links Bra\u0219ov and \u00centorsura Buz\u0103ului which goes through a long tunnel (about 10 minutes) that crosses the \u00centorsurii Mountains.\n\n== Local festival ==\n\nThe ''Ciob\u0103na\u0219ul'' ({{lang-en|Little Shepherd}}) Annual Festival takes place in \u00centorsura Buz\u0103ului in the first Sunday of September and lasts for two days. At the festival, visitors come from the town and the surrounding villages, and even from other counties. In 2006, Romanian President [[Traian B\u0103sescu]] attended the festival. During the festival the attendants can consume Romanian traditional foods and drinks and are entertained with Romanian folk music.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:RO CV DN10 Intorsura Buzaului.jpg|Representation of local streets\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{commons category|\u00centorsura Buz\u0103ului}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Covasna County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Intorsura Buzaului}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Covasna County]]\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Monotowns in Romania]]\n", "text_old": "{{morerefs|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Covasna\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Covasna County\n|subdivisions           = \n|official_name=\u00centorsura Buz\u0103ului\n|image_skyline=Panorama_intorsura_buzaului_covasna_romania.jpg\n|image_shield=ROU CV Intorsura Buzaului CoA1.jpg\n|image_map=Intorsatura Buzaului jud Covasna.png\n|coordinates      = {{coord|45|40|22|N|26|2|3|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|leader_party=PSD\n|leader_name=Leca B\u0103ncil\u0103\n|area_total_km2=60\n|website={{url|http://www.intorsura.info/}}\n}}\n'''\u00centorsura Buz\u0103ului''' ({{lang-hu|Bodzafordul\u00f3}} {{IPA-hu|\u02c8bodd\u0361z\u0252fordulo\u02d0||Bodzafordul\u00f3.ogg}}) is  a town in [[Covasna County]], [[Transylvania]], [[Romania]]. It administers three villages: Br\u0103det (''Bred\u00e9t''), Floroaia (''Vir\u00e1gospatak'') and Scr\u0103doasa.\n\n== Population ==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1977 |6541\n|1992 |8626\n|2002 |9081\n|2011 |7319\n}}\n\nAt the 2011 Romanian census, the town had 7319 inhabitants, of whom 7265 were [[Romanians]], 37 were [[Hungarian people|Hungarians]], and 12 [[Romani people|Romani]].<ref>[http://www.edrc.ro/recensamant.jsp?regiune_id=2568&judet_id=2699&localitate_id=2704 2002 Census data for \u00centorsura Buz\u0103ului]</ref>\n\n''Demographic movement according to the censuses:''\n<timeline>\nColors=\n  id:lightgrey value:gray(0.9)\n  id:darkgrey  value:gray(0.7)\n  id:sfondo value:rgb(1,1,1)\n  id:barra value:rgb(0.6,0.7,0.8)\n\nImageSize  = width:280 height:220\nPlotArea   = left:50 bottom:50 top:30 right:30\n